feminine of 376 or 582; irregular plural, nashiym {naw-sheem'}; a woman (used in the same wide sense as 582):--(adulter)ess, each, every, female, X many, + none, one, + together, wife, woman. Often unexpressed in English.
feminine passive participle from an unused root meaning to found; foundation:--foundation.

or iAshshur {ash-shoor'}; apparently from 833 (in the sense of successful); Ashshur, the second son of Shem; also his descendants and the country occupied by them (i.e. Assyria), its region and its empire:--Asshur, Assur, Assyria, Assyrians. See 838.
or iAshshuwriy {ash-shoo-ree'}; from a patrial word of the same form as 804; an Ashurite (collectively) or inhabitant of Ashur, a district in Palestine:--Asshurim, Ashurites.
probably from 7835; black; Ashchur, an Israelite:--Ashur.
of foreign origin; Ashima, a deity of Hamath:--Ashima.
from the same as 784 (in the sense of pressing down firmly; compare 803); a (ruined) foundation:--foundation.
feminine of 808; something closely pressed together, i.e. a cake of raisins or other comfits:--flagon.
from an unused root (probably meaning to bunch together); a testicle (as a lump):--stone.
or meshkol {esh-kole'}; probably prolonged from 810; a bunch of grapes or other fruit:--cluster (of grapes).
the same as 811; Eshcol, the name of an Amorite, also of a valley in Palestine:--Eshcol.
of foreign origin; Ashkenaz, a Japhethite, also his descendants:--Ashkenaz.
for 7939; a gratuity:--gift, present.
from a root of uncertain signification; a tamarisk tree; by extension, a grove of any kind:--grove, tree.

or mashem {aw-shame'}; a primitive root; to be guilty; by implication to be punished or perish:--X certainly, be(-come, made) desolate, destroy, X greatly, be(-come, found, hold) guilty, offend (acknowledge offence), trespass.
from 816; guilt; by implication, a fault; also a sin-offering:--guiltiness, (offering for) sin, trespass (offering).
from 816; guilty; hence, presenting a sin- offering:--one which is faulty, guilty.
feminine of 817; guiltiness, a fault, the presentation of a sin-offering:--offend, sin, (cause of) trespass(-ing, offering).
probably from 8081; a fat-field:--desolate place.
or bashmuwrah {ash-moo-raw'}; or -ashmoreth {ash-mo'-reth}; (feminine) from 8104; a night watch:--watch.
apparently from an unused root (probably meaning to leave interstices); A latticed window:--casement, lattice.
probably a variation for 3466; Ashnah, the name of two places in Palestine:--Ashnah.
from 8172; support; Eshan, a place in Palestine:--Eshean.
from an unused root (probably meaning to lisp, i.e. practice enchantment); a conjurer:--astrologer.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 825:--astrologer.
perhaps (feminine) from the same as 825 (in the sense of covering); a quiver or arrow-case:--quiver.
of foreign origin; Ashpenaz, a Babylonian eunuch:--Ashpenaz.
of uncertain derivation; a measured portion:--good piece (of flesh).
or uashpowth {ash-pohth'}; or (contraction) shphoth {shef-ohth'}; plural of a noun of the same form as 827, from 8192 (in the sense of scraping); a heap of rubbish or filth:--dung (hill).
probably from 8254 in the sense of weighing-place (i.e. mart); Ashkelon, a place in Palestine:--Ashkelon, Askalon.
patrial from 831; Ashkelonite (collectively) or inhabitant of Ashkelon:--Eshkalonites.

or rasher {aw-share'}; a primitive root; to be straight (used in the widest sense, especially to be level, right, happy); figuratively, to go forward, be honest, proper:--(call, be) bless(-ed, happy), go, guide, lead, relieve.

a primitive relative pronoun (of every gender and number); who, which, what, that; also (as an adverb and a conjunction) when, where, how, because, in order that, etc.:--X after, X alike, as (soon as), because, X every, for, + forasmuch, + from whence, + how(-soever), X if, (so) that ((thing) which, wherein), X though, + until, + whatsoever, when, where (+ -as, -in, -of, -on, -soever, -with), which, whilst, + whither(- soever), who(-m, -soever, -se). As it is indeclinable, it is often accompanied by the personal pronoun expletively, used to show the connection.
from 833; happiness; only in masculine plural construction as interjection, how happy!:--blessed, happy.
from 833, happy; Asher, a son of Jacob, and the tribe descended from him, with its territory; also a place in Palestine:--Asher
from 833; happiness:--happy.
or ashshur {ash-shoor'}; from 833 in the sense of going; a step:--going, step.
contracted for 8391; the cedar tree or some other light elastic wood:--Ashurite.
by orthographical variation from 833 and 410; right of God; Asarel, an Israelite:--Asareel.
from the same as 840; right toward God; Asarelah, an Israelite:--Asarelah. Compare 3480.
or masheyrah {ash-ay-raw'}; from 833; happy; Asherah (or Astarte) a Phoenician goddess; also an image of the same:-- grove. Compare 6253.
patronymic from 836; an Asherite (collectively) or descendant of Asher:--Asherites.
an orthographical variation for 840; Asriel, the name of two Israelites:--Ashriel, Asriel.
patronymic from 844; an Asrielite (collectively) or descendant of Asriel:--Asrielites.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to 833; a wall (from its uprightness):--wall.
or mEshtafowl {esh-taw-ole'}; probably from 7592; intreaty; Eshtaol, a place in Palestine:--Eshtaol.
patrial from 847; an Eshtaolite (collectively) or inhabitant of Eshtaol:--Eshtaulites.
(Aramaic) from 7712 (in a bad sense); rebellion:--sedition.
probably from the same as 7764; restful; Eshton, an Israelite:--Eshton.
or bEshtmowam {esh-tem-o'-ah}; or sEshtmoh {esh-tem-o'}; from 8085 (in the sense of obedience); Eshtemoa or Eshtemoh, a place in Palestine:--Eshtemoa, Eshtemoh.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 226; a portent:--sign.

apparent contracted from 226 in the demonstrative sense of entity; properly, self (but generally used to point out more definitely the object of a verb or preposition, even or namely):--(as such unrepresented in English).

probably from 579; properly, nearness (used only as a preposition or an adverb), near; hence, generally, with, by, at, among, etc.:--against, among, before, by, for, from, in(-to), (out) of, with. Often with another prepositional prefix.
of uncertain derivation; a hoe or other digging implement:--coulter, plowshare.
from 854 and 1168; with Baal; Ethbaal, a Phoenician king:--Ethbaal.
or matha {aw-thaw'}; a primitive root (collateral to 225 contraction); to arrive:--(be-, things to) come (upon), bring.
(Aramaic) or wathaw (Aramaic) {aw-thaw'}; corresponding to 857:--(be-)come, bring.

or (shortened); aatta {at-taw'}; or wath {ath}; feminine (irregular) sometimes nattiy {at-tee'}; plural masculine attem {at- tem'}; feminine atten {at-ten'}; or oattenah {at-tay'naw}; or fattennah {at-tane'-naw}; a primitive pronoun of the second person; thou and thee, or (plural) ye and you:--thee, thou, ye, you.
probably from the same as 386 (in the sense of patience); a female donkey (from its docility):--(she) ass.
(Aramaic) probably from the corresponding to 784; probably a fire-place, i.e. furnace:--furnace.
or mattiyq {at-teek'}; from 5423 in the sense of decreasing; a ledge or offset in a building:--gallery.
or tIythay {ee-thah'ee}; from 854; near; Ittai or Ithai, the name of a Gittite and of an Israelite:--Ithai, Ittai.
of Egyptian derivation; Etham, a place in the Desert:--Etham.
or tithmowl {ith-mole'}; or methmuwl {eth- mool'}; probably from 853 or 854 and 4136; heretofore; definitely yesterday:--+ before (that) time, + heretofore, of late (old), + times past, yester(day).
from 8566; a present (as the price of harlotry):--reward.
perhaps from 866; munificence; Ethni, an Israelite:--Ethni.
the same as 866; a gift (as the price of harlotry or idolatry):--hire, reward.
the same as 868 in the sense of 867; Ethnan, an Israelite:--Ethnan.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to that of 871; a place; (adverb) after:--after, place.
plural from an unused root (probably meaning to step); places; Atharim, a place near Palestine:--spies.
from 935; an entrance to a building:--entry.
(Aramaic) from 888; wicked:--bad.
a primitive root; to dig; by analogy, to engrave; figuratively, to explain:--declare, (make) plain(-ly).
from 874; a pit; especially a well:--pit, well.
the same as 875; Beer, a place in the Desert, also one in Palestine:--Beer.
from 874; a cistern:--cistern.
from 875; a well; Beera, an Israelite:--Beera.
from 875 and the plural of 410; well of heroes; Beer-Elim, a place in the Desert:--Beer-elim.
the same as 878; Beerah, an Israelite:--Beerah.
feminine plural of 875; wells; Beeroth, a place in Palestine:--Beeroth.
from 875; fountained; Beeri, the name of a Hittite and of an Israelite:--Beeri.

i.u: 883 B'er la-Chay Ro'iy be-ayr' lakh-ah'ee ro-ee'

lexicon.i: from 875 and 2416 (with prefix) and 7203; well of a living (One) my Seer; Beer-Lachai-Roi, a place in the Desert:--Beer-lahai-roi.
from 875 and 7651 (in the sense of 7650); well of an oath; Beer-Sheba, a place in Palestine:--Beer-shebah.
from the feminine plural of 875, and the plural contraction of 1121, and 3292; wells of (the) sons of Jaakan; Beeroth-Bene-Jaakan, a place in the Desert:--Beeroth of the children of Jaakan.
patrial from 881; a Beerothite or inhabitant of Beeroth:--Beerothite.
a primitive root; to smell bad; figuratively, to be offensive morally:--(make to) be abhorred (had in abomination, loathsome, odious), (cause a, make to) stink(-ing savour), X utterly.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 887:--displease.
from 877; a stench:--stink.
feminine of 889; stink-weed or any other noxious or useless plant:--cockle.
plural of 889; poison-berries:--wild grapes.
feminine active participle of an unused root meaning to hollow out; something hollowed (as a gate), i.e. pupil of the eye:--apple (of the eye).
probably of foreign origin; Bebai, an Israelite:--Bebai.
from 1101; confusion; Babel (i.e. Babylon), including Babylonia and the Babylonian empire:--Babel, Babylon.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 894:--Babylon.
(Aramaic) patrial from 895; a Babylonian:--Babylonia.
a Persian word; food:--spoil (from the margin for 957.)

a primitive root; to cover (with a garment); figuratively, to act covertly; by implication, to pillage:--deal deceitfully (treacherously, unfaithfully), offend, transgress(-or), (depart), treacherous (dealer, -ly, man), unfaithful(-ly, man), X very.
from 898; a covering, i.e. clothing; also treachery or pillage:--apparel, cloth(-es, ing), garment, lap, rag, raiment, robe, X very (treacherously), vesture, wardrobe.
feminine plural active participle of 898; treacheries:--treacherous.
from 898; treacherous:--treacherous.
probably of foreign origin; Bigvai, an Israelite:--Bigvai.
of Persian derivation; Bigtha, a eunuch of Xerxes:--Bigtha.
or Bigthanad {big-thaw'naw}; of similar derivation to 903; Bigthan or Bigthana, a eunuch of Xerxes:--Bigthan, Bigthana.

from 909; properly, separation; by implication, a part of the body, branch of a tree, bar for carrying; figuratively, chief of a city; especially (with prepositional prefix) as an adverb, apart, only, besides:--alone, apart, bar, besides, branch, by self, of each alike, except, only, part, staff, strength.
perhaps from 909 (in the sense of divided fibres); flaxen thread or yarn; hence, a linen garment:--linen.
from 908; a brag or lie; also a liar:--liar, lie.
a primitive root; (figuratively) to invent:--devise, feign.
a primitive root; to divide, i.e. (reflex.) be solitary:--alone.
from 909; separate; adverb, separately:--alone, desolate, only, solitary.
from 909; separation; Bedad, an Edomite:--Bedad.
probably a shortened form 5662; servant of Jehovah; Bedejah, an Israelite:--Bedeiah.
from 914; alloy (because removed by smelting); by analogy, tin:--+ plummet, tin.

a primitive root; to divide (in variation senses literally or figuratively, separate, distinguish, differ, select, etc.):-- (make, put) difference, divide (asunder), (make) separate (self, -ation), sever (out), X utterly.
from 914; a part:--piece.
probably from 914; something in pieces, i.e. bdellium, a (fragrant) gum (perhaps amber); others a pearl:--bdellium.
probably shortened for 5658; servile; Bedan, the name of two Israelites:--Bedan.
a primitive root; to gap open; used only as a denominative from 919; to mend a breach:--repair.
from 918; a gap or leak (in a building or a ship):--breach, + calker.
probably from 1856 with a prepositional prefix; by stabbing, i.e. assassin; Bidkar, an Israelite:--Bidkar.
(Aramaic) corresponding (by transposition) to 6504; to scatter:--scatter.
from an unused root (meaning to be empty); a vacuity, i.e. (superficially) an undistinguishable ruin:--emptiness, void.
from an unused root (probably meaning to glisten); white marble or perhaps alabaster:--red (marble).
(Aramaic) from 927; a hurry; only adverb, hastily:--in haste.
from an unused root (meaning to be bright); shining:--bright.

a primitive root; to tremble inwardly (or palpitate), i.e. (figuratively) be (causative, make) (suddenly) alarmed or agitated; by implication to hasten anxiously:--be (make) affrighted (afraid, amazed, dismayed, rash), (be, get, make) haste(-n, -y, -ily), (give) speedy(-ily), thrust out, trouble, vex.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 926; to terrify, hasten:--in haste, trouble.
from 926; panic, destruction:--terror, trouble.
from an unused root (probably meaning to be mute); properly, a dumb beast; especially any large quadruped or animal (often collective):--beast, cattle.
in form a plural or 929, but really a singular of Egyptian derivation; a water-ox, i.e. the hippopotamus or Nile- horse:--Behemoth.
from an unused root apparently meaning to be thick; the thumb of the hand or great toe of the foot:--thumb, great toe.
an orthographical variation of 931; thumb, Bohan, an Israelite:--Bohan.
from an unused root meaning to be pale; white scurf:--freckled spot.
feminine active participle of the same as 925; a whitish spot on the skin:--bright spot.

a primitive root; to go or come (in a wide variety of applications):--abide, apply, attain, X be, befall, + besiege, bring (forth, in, into, to pass), call, carry, X certainly, (cause, let, thing for) to come (against, in, out, upon, to pass), depart, X doubtless again, + eat, + employ, (cause to) enter (in, into, -tering, -trance, -try), be fallen, fetch, + follow, get, give, go (down, in, to war), grant, + have, X indeed, (in-)vade, lead, lift (up), mention, pull in, put, resort, run (down), send, set, X (well) stricken (in age), X surely, take (in), way.
a primitive root; to disrespect:--contemn, despise, X utterly.
from 936; disrespect:--contempt(-uously), despised, shamed.
the same as 937; Buz, the name of a son of Nahor, and of an Israelite:--Buz.
feminine passive participle of 936; something scorned; an object of contempt:--despised.
patronymic from 938; a Buzite or descendant of Buz:--Buzite.
the same as 940; Buzi, an Israelite:--Buzi.
probably of Persian origin; Bavvai, an Israelite:--Bavai.
a primitive root; to involve (literally or figuratively):--be entangled, (perplexed).
for 2981; produce (of the earth, etc.):--food, stock.
the same as 944 (in the sense of rain); Bul, the eighth Hebrew month:--Bul.
from 995; discretion; Bunah, an Israelite:--Bunah.
a primitive root; to trample (literally or figuratively):--loath, tread (down, under (foot)), be polluted.
from an unused root (of the same form) meaning to bleach, i.e. (intransitive) be white; probably cotton (of some sort):--fine (white) linen.
from the same as 948; shining; Botsets, a rock near Michmash:--Bozez.
feminine passive participle of an unused root (meaning to be hollow); emptiness (as adjective):--empty.
properly, active participle from 1239 as denominative from 1241; a cattle-tender:--herdman.
a primitive root; to bore, i.e. (figuratively) examine:--declare.
from 952 (in the sense of 877); a pit hole (especially one used as a cistern or a prison):--cistern, dungeon, fountain, pit, well.

a primitive root; properly, to pale, i.e. by implication to be ashamed; also (by implication) to be disappointed or delayed:--(be, make, bring to, cause, put to, with, a-)shamed(-d), be (put to) confounded(-fusion), become dry, delay, be long.
feminine participle passive of 954; shame:--shame.
(Aramaic) apparent denominative from 1005; to lodge over night:--pass the night.
from 962; plunder:--booty, prey, spoil(-ed).
a primitive root; probably to cleave:--spoil.
a primitive root; to disesteem:--despise, disdain, contemn(-ptible), + think to scorn, vile person.
from 959; scorned:--despise.
feminine of 957; booty:--prey, spoil.
a primitive root; to plunder:--catch, gather, (take) for a prey, rob(-ber), spoil, take (away, spoil), X utterly.
from 959:--disesteem:--contempt.
from 959 and 3050; contempts of Jah; Bizjothjah, a place in Palestine:--Bizjothjah.
from an unused root meaning to lighten; a flash of lightning:--flash of lightning.
from 965; lightning; Bezek, a place in Palestine:--Bezek.
a primitive root; to disperse:--scatter.
of Persian origin; Biztha, a eunuch of Xerxes:--Biztha.
from 974; an assayer or metals:--tower.
or bachur {baw-khoor'}; participle passive of 977; properly, selected, i.e. a youth (often collective):--(choice) young (man), chosen, X hole.
another form of 975; a watch-tower of besiegers:--tower.
from 977; select:--choose, chosen one, elect.
a primitive root; to loath:--abhor, get hastily (from the margin for 926).
a primitive root; to test (especially metals); generally and figuratively, to investigate:--examine, prove, tempt, try (trial).
from 974 (in the sense of keeping a look-out); a watch-tower:--tower.
from 974; trial:--tried.
a primitive root; properly, to try, i.e. (by implication) select:--acceptable, appoint, choose (choice), excellent, join, be rather, require.
patrial from 980 (by transposition); a Bacharumite or inhabitant of Bachurim:--Baharumite.
or bchuwrowth {bekh-oo-roth'}; feminine plural of 970; also (masculine plural) bchuriym {bekh-oo-reem'}; youth (collectively and abstractly):--young men, youth.
or Bachuwriym {bakh-oo-reem'}; masculine plural of 970; young men; Bachurim, a place in Palestine:--Bahurim.
or batah {baw-taw'}; a primitive root; to babble; hence, to vociferate angrily:--pronounce, speak (unadvisedly).

a primitive root; properly, to hie for refuge (but not so precipitately as 2620); figuratively, to trust, be confident or sure:--be bold (confident, secure, sure), careless (one, woman), put confidence, (make to) hope, (put, make to) trust.

from 982; properly, a place of refuge; abstract, safety, both the fact (security) and the feeling (trust); often (adverb with or without preposition) safely:--assurance, boldly, (without) care(- less), confidence, hope, safe(-ly, -ty), secure, surely.
the same as 983; Betach, a place in Syria:--Betah.
feminine of 984; trust:--confidence.
from 982; trust:--confidence, hope.
feminine plural from 982; security:--secure.
a primitive root; to desist from labor:--cease.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 988; to stop:--(cause, make to), cease, hinder.
from an unused root probably meaning to be hollow; the belly, especially the womb; also the bosom or body of anything:-- belly, body, + as they be born, + within, womb.
the same as 990; Beten. a place in Palestine:--Beten.
from 990; (only in plural) a pistachio-nut (from its form):--nut.
probably plural from 992; hollows: Betonim, a place in Palestine:--Betonim.
perhaps from 1158 (in the sense of asking); properly, a request; used only adverbially (always with "my Lord"); Oh that!; with leave, or if it please:--alas, O, oh.

a primitive root; to separate mentally (or distinguish), i.e.(generally) understand:--attend, consider, be cunning, diligently, direct, discern, eloquent, feel, inform, instruct, have intelligence, know, look well to, mark, perceive, be prudent, regard, (can) skill(-full), teach, think, (cause, make to, get, give, have) understand(-ing), view, (deal) wise(-ly, man).

(sometimes in the plural masculine or feminine); properly, the constructive form of an otherwise unused noun from 995; a distinction; but used only as a prep, between (repeated before each noun, often with other particles); also as a conjunction, either...or:--among, asunder, at, between (-twixt...and), + from (the widest), X in, out of, whether (it be...or), within.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 996:--among, between.
from 995; understanding:--knowledge, meaning, X perfectly, understanding, wisdom.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 998:--knowledge.
from the same as 948; an egg (from its whiteness):--egg.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1002; a palace:--palace.
of foreign origin; a castle or palace:--palace.
from 1002; a fortress:--castle.

probably from 1129 abbreviated; a house (in the greatest variation of applications, especially family, etc.):--court, daughter, door, + dungeon, family, + forth of, X great as would contain, hangings, home(born), (winter)house(-hold), inside(-ward), palace, place, + prison, + steward, + tablet, temple, web, + within(-out).
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1004:--house.
the same as 1004; Bajith, a place in Palestine:--Bajith.
from 1004 and 205; house of vanity; Beth- Aven, a place in Palestine:--Beth-aven.
from 1004 and 410; house of God; Beth-El, a place in Palestine:--Beth-el.
from 1004 and 695 and 410; house of God's ambush; Beth-Arbel, a place in Palestine:--Beth-Arbel.

i.u: 1010 Beyth Ba`al M`own bayth bah'-al me-own'

lexicon.i: from 1004 and 1168 and 4583; house of Baal of (the) habitation of (apparently by transposition); or (shorter) Beyth M own {bayth me-own'}; house of habitation of (Baal); Beth- Baal-Meon, a place in Palestine:--Beth-baal-meon. Compare 1186 and 1194.
from 1004 and 1254; house of a creative one; Beth-Biri, a place in Palestine:--Beth-birei.
probably from 1004 and 5679; house of (the) ford; Beth-Barah, a place in Palestine:--Beth-barah.
from 1004 and 1447; house of (the) wall; Beth-Gader, a place in Palestine:--Beth-gader.
from 1004 and the passive participle of 1576; house of (the) weaned; Beth-Gamul, a place East of the Jordan:--Beth- gamul.
from 1004 and the dual of 1690; house of (the) two figcakes; Beth-Diblathajim, a place East of the Jordan:--Beth-diblathaim.
from 1004 and 1712; house of Dagon; Beth-Dagon, the name of two places in Palestine:--Beth-dagon.
patrial from 1008 with the article interposed; a Beth-elite, or inhabitant of Bethel:--Bethelite.
from 1004 and 681 with the article interposed; house of the side; Beth-ha-Etsel, a place in Palestine:--Beth- ezel.
from 1004 and 1537 with the article interposed; house of Gilgal (or rolling); Beth-hag-Gilgal, a place in Palestine:--Beth-gilgal.
from 1004 and the plural of 3451 with the article interposed; house of the deserts; Beth-ha- Jeshimoth, a town East of the Jordan:--Beth-jeshimoth.
from 1004 and 3754 with the article interposed; house of the vineyard; Beth-hak-Kerem, a place in Palestine:--Beth-haccerem.
patrial from 1035 with the article inserted; a Beth-lechemite, or native of Bethlechem:--Bethlehemite.
from 1004 and 4801 with the article interposed; house of the breadth; Beth-ham-Merchak, a place in Palestine:--place that was far off.

or (shortened) Beyth Mar-kabowth {bayth mar-kaw-both'}; from 1004 and the plural of 4818 (with or without the article interposed); place of (the) chariots; Beth-ham-Markaboth or Beth-Markaboth, a place in Palestine:--Beth-marcaboth.
from 1004 and 6010 with the article interposed; house of the valley; Beth-ha-Emek, a place in Palestine:--Beth- emek.
from 1004 and 6160 with the article interposed; house of the Desert; Beth-ha-Arabah, a place in Palestine:--Beth-arabah.
from 1004 and 7311 with the article interposed; house of the height; Beth-ha-Ram, a place East of the Jordan:--Beth-aram.
probably for 1027; Beth-ha-Ram, a place East of the Jordan:--Beth-haran.
from 1004 and 7848 with the article interposed; house of the acacia; Beth-hash-Shittah, a place in Palestine:--Beth-shittah.
patrial from 1053 with the article inserted; a Beth-shimshite, or inhabitant of Bethshemesh:--Bethshemite.
from 1004 and the same as 2295; house of a partridge; Beth-Choglah, a place in Palestine:--Beth-hoglah.
from 1004 and 2356; house of hollowness; Beth-Choron, the name of two adjoining places in Palestine:--Beth- horon.
from 1004 and 3733; house of pasture; Beth-Car, a place in Palestine:--Beth-car.
from 1004 and the plural of 3833; house of lionesses; Beth-Lebaoth, a place in Palestine:--Beth-lebaoth. Compare 3822.
from 1004 and 3899; house of bread; Beth- Lechem, a place in Palestine:--Beth-lehem.
from 1004 and the feminine of 6083 (with preposition interposed); house to (i.e. of) dust; Beth-le-Aphrah, a place in Palestine:--house of Aphrah.
or Beyth Mil-loh {bayth mil-lo'}; from 1004 and 4407; house of (the) rampart; Beth-Millo, the name of two citadels:-- house of Millo.
from 1004 and 4601; house of Maakah; Beth-Maakah, a place in Palestine:--Beth-maachah.
from 1004 and the feminine of 5246; house of (the) leopard; Beth-Nimrah, a place east of the Jordan:--Beth-Nimrah. Compare 5247.
from 1004 and 5730; house of pleasure; Beth-Eden, a place in Syria:--Beth-eden.
from 1004 and 5820; house of Azmaveth, a place in Palestine:--Beth-az-maveth. Compare 5820.
from 1004 and a plural from 6030; house of replies; Beth-Anoth, a place in Palestine:--Beth-anoth.
an orthographical variation for 1042; Beth-Anath, a place in Palestine:--Beth-anath.
from 1004 and a derivative of 6123; house of (the) binding (for sheep-shearing); Beth-Eked, a place in Palestine:-- shearing house.
: from 1004 and 6252; house of Ashtoreths; Beth-Ashtaroth, a place in Palestine:--house of Ashtaroth. Compare 1203, 6252.
from 1004 and 6412; house of escape; Beth- Palet, a place in Palestine:--Beth-palet.
from 1004 and 6465; house of Peor; Beth- Peor, a place East of the Jordan:--Beth-peor.
from 1004 and a derivative from 6327; house of dispersion; Beth-Patstsets, a place in Palestine:--Beth-pazzez.
from 1004 and 6697; house of (the) rock; Beth-Tsur, a place in Palestine:--Beth-zur.
from 1004 and 7339; house of (the) street; Beth-Rechob, a place in Palestine:--Beth-rehob.
from 1004 and 7497; house of (the) giant; Beth-Rapha, an Israelite:--Beth-rapha.
or Beyth Shan {bayth shawn'}; from 1004 and 7599; house of ease; Beth-Shean or Beth-Shan, a place in Palestine:--Beth- shean, Beth-Shan.
from 1004 and 8121; house of (the) sun; Beth-Shemesh, a place in Palestine:--Beth-shemesh.
from 1004 and 8598; house of (the) apple; Beth-Tappuach, a place in Palestine:--Beth-tappuah.
probably from 1004; a palace (i.e. large house):--palace.
from 1058, weeping; Baca, a valley in Palestine:--Baca.
the same as 1056; the weeping tree (some gum- distilling tree, perhaps the balsam):--mulberry tree.
a primitive root; to weep; generally to bemoan:--X at all, bewail, complain, make lamentation, X more, mourn, X sore, X with tears, weep.
from 1058; a weeping:--X sore.
from 1069; firstborn; hence, chief:--eldest (son), firstborn(-ling).
from 1069; the first-fruits of the crop:--first fruit (-ripe (figuratively)), hasty fruit.
or (short) bkorah {bek-o-raw'}; feminine of 1060; the firstling of man or beast; abstractly primogeniture:--birthright, firstborn(-ling).
feminine of 1061; the early fig:--firstripe (fruit).
feminine of 1062; primogeniture; Bekorath, an Israelite:--Bechorath.
from 1058; a weeping; by analogy, a dripping:--overflowing, X sore, (continual) weeping, wept.
plural active participle of 1058; (with the article) the weepers; Bo-kim, a place in Palestine:--Bochim.
feminine from 1069; the eldest daughter:--firstborn.
from 1058; a weeping:--mourning.

a primitive root; properly, to burst the womb, i.e. (causatively) bear or make early fruit (of woman or tree); also (as denominative from 1061) to give the birthright:--make firstborn, be firstling, bring forth first child (new fruit).
from 1069 (in the sense of youth); a young camel:-- dromedary.
the same as 1070; Beker, the name of two Israelites:-- Becher.
feminine of 1070; a young she-camel:--dromedary.
by orthographical variation for 1063; a first- ripe fig:--firstripe.
from 1069; first-born; Bokeru, an Israelite:--Bocheru.
from 1069; youth-ful; Bikri, an Israelite:--Bichri.
patronymically from 1071; a Bakrite (collectively) or descendants of Beker:--Bachrites.
from 1086; properly, a failure; by implication nothing; usually (adverb) not at all; also lest:--lest, neither, no, none (that...), not (any), nothing.
by contraction for 1168; Bel, the Baal of the Babylonians:-- Bel.
(Aramaic) from 1080; properly, anxiety, i.e. (by implication) the heart (as its seat):--heart.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1086 (but used only in a mental sense); to afflict:--wear out.
from 1078 and 113 (contracted); Bel (is his) lord; Baladan, the name of a Babylonian prince:--Baladan.
a primitive root; to break off or loose (in a favorable or unfavorable sense), i.e. desist (from grief) or invade (with destruction):--comfort, (recover) strength(-en).
from 1082; desistance; Bilgah, the name of two Israelites:--Bilgah.
from 1082; desistant; Bilgai, an Israelite:--Bilgai.
of uncertain derivation; Bildad, one of Job's friends:--Bildad.
a primitive root; to fail; by implication to wear out, decay (causatively, consume, spend):--consume, enjoy long, become (make, wax) old, spend, waste.
from 1086; worn out:--old.
feminine of 1087; failure; Balah, a place in Palestine:--Balah.
a primitive root (rather by transposition for 926); to palpitate; hence, (causatively) to terrify:--trouble.
from 1089; timid; Bilhah, the name of one of Jacob's concubines; also of a place in Palestine:--Bilhah.
from 1089; alarm; hence, destruction:--terror, trouble.
from 1089; timid; Bilhan, the name of an Edomite and of an Israelite:--Bilhan.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to 1086; excise (on articles consumed):--tribute.
or (fully) blowy {bel-o'ee}; from 1086; (only in plural construction) rags:--old.
of foreign derivation; Belteshatstsar, the Babylonian name of Daniel:--Belteshazzar.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1095:--Belteshazzar.

from 1086; properly, failure, i.e. nothing or destruction; usually (with preposition) without, not yet, because not, as long as, etc.:--corruption, ig(norantly), for lack of, where no...is, so that no, none, not, un(awares), without.
from 1101; mixed, i.e. (specifically) feed (for cattle):--corn, fodder, provender.
from 1097 and 4100; (as indef.) nothing whatever:--nothing.
from 1097 and 3276; without profit, worthlessness; by extension, destruction, wickedness (often in connection with 376, 802, 1121, etc.):--Belial, evil, naughty, ungodly (men), wicked.
a primitive root; to overflow (specifically with oil.); by implication, to mix; also (denominatively from 1098) to fodder:--anoint, confound, X fade, mingle, mix (self), give provender, temper.
a primitive root; to muzzle:--be held in.
a primitive root; to pinch sycamore figs (a process necessary to ripen them):--gatherer.
a primitive root; to make away with (specifically by swallowing); generally, to destroy:--cover, destroy, devour, eat up, be at end, spend up, swallow down (up).
from 1104; a gulp; figuratively, destruction:--devouring, that which he hath swallowed up.
the same as 1105; Bela, the name of a place, also of an Edomite and of two Israelites:--Bela.
or balmadey {bal-ad-ay'}; constructive plural from 1077 and 5703, not till, i.e. (as preposition or adverb) except, without, besides:--beside, not (in), save, without.
patronymically from 1106: a Belaite (collectively) or descendants of Bela:--Belaites.
probably from 1077 and 5971; not (of the) people, i.e. foreigner; Bilam, a Mesopotamian prophet; also a place in Palestine:--Balaam, Bileam.
a primitive root; to annihilate:--(make) waste.
from 1110; waster; Balak, a Moabitish king:--Balak.
or Belshatstsar {bale-shats-tsar'}; of foreign origin (compare 1095); Belshatstsar, a Babylonian king:--Belshazzar.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1112:--Belshazzar.
of uncertain derivation; Bilshan, an Israelite:--Bilshan.

constructive feminine of 1086 (equivalent to 1097); properly, a failure of, i.e. (used only as a negative particle, usually with a prepositional prefix) not, except, without, unless, besides, because not, until, etc.:--because un(satiable), beside, but, + continual, except, from, lest, neither, no more, none, not, nothing, save, that no, without.
from an unused root (meaning to be high); an elevation:--height, high place, wave.
the same as 1116; Bamah, a place in Palestine:--Bamah. See also 1120.
probably from 4107 with prepositional prefix; with pruning; Bimhal, an Israelite:--Bimhal.
prolongation for prepositional prefix; in, with, by, etc.:--for, in into, through.
plural of 1116; heights; or (fully) Bamowth Bahal {baw-moth' bah'-al}; from the same and 1168; heights of Baal; Bamoth or Bamoth-Baal, a place East of the Jordan:--Bamoth, Bamoth-baal.

from 1129; a son (as a builder of the family name), in the widest sense (of literal and figurative relationship, including grandson, subject, nation, quality or condition, etc., (like 1, 251, etc.)):--+ afflicted, age, (Ahoh-) (Ammon-) (Hachmon-) (Lev-)ite, (anoint-)ed one, appointed to, (+) arrow, (Assyr-) (Babylon-) (Egypt-) (Grec-)ian, one born, bough, branch, breed, + (young) bullock, + (young) calf, X came up in, child, colt, X common, X corn, daughter, X of first, + firstborn, foal, + very fruitful, + postage, X in, + kid, + lamb, (+) man, meet, + mighty, + nephew, old, (+) people, + rebel, + robber, X servant born, X soldier, son, + spark, + steward, + stranger, X surely, them of, + tumultuous one, + valiant(-est), whelp, worthy, young (one), youth.
the same as 1121; Ben, an Israelite:--Ben.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1121:--child, son, young.
(Aramaic) or bnah (Aramaic) {ben-aw'}; corresponding to 1129; to build:--build, make.
from 1121 and 40; (the) son of Abinadab; Ben-Abinadab, an Israelite:--the son of Abinadab.
from 1121 and 205; son of my sorrow; Ben-Oni, the original name of Benjamin:--Ben-oni.
from 1121 and 1397; son of (the) hero; Ben- Geber, an Israelite:--the son of Geber.
from 1121 and a derivative of 1856; son of piercing (or of a lance); Ben-Deker, an Israelite:--the son of Dekar.
a primitive root; to build (literally and figuratively):--(begin to) build(-er), obtain children, make, repair, set (up), X surely.
from 1121 and 1908; son of Hadad; Ben-Hadad, the name of several Syrian kings:--Ben-hadad.
from 1129; built up; Binnui, an Israelite:--Binnui.
from 1121 and 2105; son of Zocheth; Ben- Zocheth, an Israelite:--Ben-zoketh.
from 1121 and 2354; son of Chur; Ben-Chur, an Israelite:--the son of Hur.
from 1121 and 2428; son of might; Ben-Chail, an Israelite:--Ben-hail.
from 1121 and 2605; son of Chanan; Ben- Chanan, an Israelite:--Ben-hanan.
from 1121 and 2617; son of kindness; Ben- Chesed, an Israelite:--the son of Hesed.
from 1129; built; Bani, the name of five Israelites:--Bani.
or (fuller) Buwniy {boo-nee'}; from 1129; built; Bunni or Buni, an Israelite:--Bunni.
from the plural construction of 1121 and 1300; sons of lightning, Bene-berak, a place in Palestine:--Bene-barak.
feminine from 1129; a structure:--building.
or (prolonged) Bnayahuw {ben-aw-yaw'-hoo}; from 1129 and 3050; Jah has built; Benajah, the name of twelve Israelites:-- Benaiah.
from the plural of 1121 and 3292; sons of Yaakan; Bene-Jaakan, a place in the Desert:--Bene-jaakan.
dual of 996; a double interval, i.e. the space between two armies:--+ champion.
from 1121 and 3225; son of (the) right hand; Binjamin, youngest son of Jacob; also the tribe descended from him, and its territory:--Benjamin.

sometimes (with the article inserted) Ben-ha-yminiy {ben-hah-yem-ee-nee'}; with 376 inserted (1 Sam. 9:1) Ben-miysh Ymiyniy {ben-eesh' yem-ee-nee'}; son of a man of Jemini; or shortened (1 Sam. 9:4; Esth. 2:5) eIysh Ymiyniy {eesh yem-ee-nee'}; a man of Jemini, or (1 Sam. 20:1) simply Yminiy {yem-ee-nee'}; a Jeminite; (plural Bniy Ymiyniy {ben- ay' yem-ee-nee'}; patron from 1144; a Benjaminite, or descendent of Benjamin:--Benjamite, of Benjamin.
from 1129; an edifice:--building.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1146:--building.
probably from 1121 with pron. suff.; our son; Beninu, an Israelite:--Beninu.
(Aramaic) of uncertain affinity; to be enraged:--be angry.
or Bincah {bin-aw'}; of uncertain derivation; Bina or Binah, an Israelite:--Binea, Bineah.
from 1121 and 5971 with pronomial suffix; son of my people; Ben-Ammi, a son of Lot:--Ben-ammi.
from 5475 and 3050 with prepositional prefix; in (the) counsel of Jehovah; Besodejah, an Israelite:--Besodeiah.
from 947; domineering; Besai, one of the Nethinim:--Besai.
from an unused root meaning to be sour; an immature grape:--unripe grape.
from the same as 1154:--sour grape.
(Aramaic) or b ah (Aramaic) {beh-aw'}; corresponding to 1158; to seek or ask:--ask, desire, make (petition), pray, request, seek.
from 5704 with prepositional prefix; in up to or over against; generally at, beside, among, behind, for, etc.:--about, at by (means of), for, over, through, up (-on), within.
a primitive root; to gush over, i.e. to swell; (figuratively) to desire earnestly; by implication to ask:--cause, inquire, seek up, swell out.
(Aramaic) from 1156; a request:--petition.
from 1197 (in the sense of burning); a lamp; Beor, the name of the father of an Edomitish king; also of that of Balaam:--Beor.
masculine plural from 1204; alarms:--terrors.
from an unused root of uncertain meaning; Boaz, the ancestor of David; also the name of a pillar in front of the temple:--Boaz.
a primitive root; to trample down, i.e. (figuratively) despise:--kick.
from 1158; a prayer:--grave.
from 1197 (in the sense of eating): cattle:--beast, cattle.
a primitive root; to be master; hence, (as denominative from 1167) to marry:--have dominion (over), be husband, marry(-ried, X wife).

from 1166; a master; hence, a husband, or (figuratively) owner (often used with another noun in modifications of this latter sense):--+ archer, + babbler, + bird, captain, chief man, + confederate, + have to do, + dreamer, those to whom it is due, + furious, those that are given to it, great, + hairy, he that hath it, have, + horseman, husband, lord, man, + married, master, person, + sworn, they of.
the same as 1167; Baal, a Phoenician deity:--Baal, (plural) Baalim.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1167:--+ chancellor.
from 1168 and 1285; Baal of (the) covenant; Baal-Berith, a special deity of the Shechemites:--Baal-berith.
from 1168 and 1409; Baal of Fortune; Baal-Gad, a place in Syria:--Baal-gad.
feminine of 1167; a mistress:--that hath, mistress.
the same as 1172; Baalah, the name of three places in Palestine:--Baalah.
from 1167 and 1995; possessor of a multitude; Baal-Hamon, a place in Palestine:--Baal-hamon.
plural of 1172; mistresses; Bealoth, a place in Palestine:--Bealoth, in Aloth (by mistake for a plural from 5927 with prepositional prefix).
from 1168 and 2070; Baal of (the) Fly; Baal-Zebub, a special deity of the Ekronites:--Baal-zebub.
from 1167 and 2603; possessor of grace; Baal-Chanan, the name of an Edomite, also of an Israelite:--Baal-hanan.
from 1167 and a modification of 2691; possessor of a village; Baal-Chatsor, a place in Palestine:--Baal-hazor.
from 1167 and 2768; possessor of Hermon; Baal-Chermon, a place in Palestine:--Baal-hermon.
from 1167 with pron. suff.; my master; Baali, a symbolical name for Jehovah:--Baali.
from the plural of 1168 and the plural of 1116; Baals of (the) heights; Baale-Bamoth, a place East of the Jordan:--lords of the high places.
from 1168 and 3045; Baal has known; Beeljada, an Israelite:--Beeliada.
from 1167 and 3050; Jah (is) master; Bealjah, an Israelite:--Bealiah.
from the plural of 1167 and 3063; masters of Judah; Baale-Jehudah, a place in Palestine:--Baale of Judah.
probably from a derivative of 5965 with prepositional prefix; in exultation; Baalis, an Ammonitish king:--Baalis.
from 1168 and 4583; Baal of (the) habitation (of) (compare 1010); Baal-Meon, a place East of the Jordan:--Baal-meon.
from 1168 and 6465; Baal of Peor; Baal-Peor, a Moabitish deity:--Baal-peor.
from 1167 and the plural of 6556; possessor of breaches; Baal-Peratsim, a place in Palestine:--Baal- perazim.
from 1168 and 6828 (in the sense of cold) (according to others an Egyptian form of Typhon, the destroyer); Baal of winter; Baal-Tsephon, a place in Eqypt:--Baal-zephon.
from 1168 and 8031; Baal of Shalishah, Baal-Shalishah, a place in Palestine:--Baal-shalisha.
a modification of 1172; mistressship; Baalath, a place in Palestine:--Baalath.
from 1172 and 875; mistress of a well; Baalath-Beer, a place in Palestine:--Baalath-beer.
from 1167 and 8558; possessor of (the) palm-tree; Baal-Tamar, a place in Palestine:--Baal-tamar.
probably a contraction of 1010; Beon, a place East of the Jordan:--Beon.
the same as 1196; Banana, the name of four Israelite:--Baana, Baanah.
from a derivative of 6031 with prepositional prefix; in affliction:--Baanah, the name of four Israelites:--Baanah.

a primitive root; to kindle, i.e. consume (by fire or by eating); also (as denominative from 1198) to be(-come) brutish:--be brutish, bring (put, take) away, burn, (cause to) eat (up), feed, heat, kindle, set ((on fire)), waste.
from 1197; properly, foot (as consumed); i.e. (by exten.) of cattle brutishness; (concretely) stupid:--brutish (person), foolish.
from 1198; brutish: Baara, an Israelitish woman:--Baara.
from 1197; a burning:--fire.
from an unused root meaning to stink; offensiveness; Basha, a king of Israel:--Baasha.
from 6213 and 3050 with a prepositional prefix; in (the) work of Jah; Baasejah, an Israelite:--Baaseiah.
from 6251 (as singular of 6252) with a prepositional prefix; with Ashtoreth; Beeshterah, a place East of the Jordan:--Beeshterah.
a primitive root; to fear:--affright, be (make) afraid, terrify, trouble.
from 1204; fear:--trouble.
probably the same as 948; mud (as whitish clay):--mire.
intensive from 1206; a swamp:--fen, mire(-ry place).
from 1219; inaccessible, i.e. lofty:--vintage (by confusion with 1210).
perhaps the same as 1153; Betsai, the name of two Israelites:--Bezai.
from 1219; clipped, i.e. the grape crop:--vintage.
from an unused root apparently meaning to peel; an onion:--onion.
probably from 6738 and 410 with a prepositional prefix; in (the) shadow (i.e. protection) of God; Betsalel, the name of two Israelites:--Bezaleel.
or Batsliyth {bats-leeth'}; from the same as 1211; a peeling; Batsluth or Batslith, an Israelite:--Bazlith, Bazluth.

a primitive root to break off, i.e. (usually) plunder; figuratively, to finish, or (intransitively) stop:--(be) covet(- ous), cut (off), finish, fulfill, gain (greedily), get, be given to (covetousness), greedy, perform, be wounded.
from 1214; plunder; by extension, gain (usually unjust):--covetousness, (dishonest) gain, lucre, profit.
a primitive root; perhaps to swell up, i.e. blister:--swell.
from 1216; dough (as swelling by fermentation):--dough, flour.
from 1216; a swell of ground; Botscath, a place in Palestine:--Bozcath, Boskath.

a primitive root; to clip off; specifically (as denominative from 1210) to gather grapes; also to be isolated (i.e. inaccessible by height or fortification):--cut off, (de-)fenced, fortify, (grape) gather(-er), mighty things, restrain, strong, wall (up), withhold.
from 1219; strictly a clipping, i.e. gold (as dug out):--gold defence.
the same as 1220, an inaccessible spot; Betser, a place in Palestine; also an Israelite:--Bezer.
another form for 1220; gold:--gold.
feminine from 1219; an enclosure, i.e. sheep fold:--Bozrah.
the same as 1223; Botsrah, a place in Edom:--Bozrah.
masculine intensive from 1219; a fortress:--stronghold.
feminine intensive from 1219; restraint (of rain), i.e. drought:--dearth, drought.
the same as 1228; Bakbuk, one of the Nethinim:--Bakbuk.
from 1238; a bottle (from the gurgling in emptying):--bottle, cruse.
from 1228 and 3050; emptying (i.e. wasting) of Jah; Bakbukjah, an Israelite:--Bakbukiah.
reduplicated from 1239; searcher; Bakbakkar, an Israelite:--Bakbakkar.
from 1238; wasteful; Bukki, the name of two Israelites:--Bukki.
from 1238 and 3050; wasting of Jah; Bukkijah, an Israelite:--Bukkiah.
from 1234; a fissure:--breach, cleft.

a primitive root; to cleave; generally, to rend, break, rip or open:--make a breach, break forth (into, out, in pieces, through, up), be ready to burst, cleave (asunder), cut out, divide, hatch, rend (asunder), rip up, tear, win.
from 1234; a section (half) of a shekel, i.e. a beka (a weight and a coin):--bekah, half a shekel.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1237:--plain.
from 1234; properly, a split, i.e. a wide level valley between mountains:--plain, valley.
a primitive root; to pour out, i.e. to empty, figuratively, to depopulate; by analogy, to spread out (as a fruitful vine):--(make) empty (out), fail, X utterly, make void.
a primitive root; properly, to plough, or (generally) break forth, i.e. (figuratively) to inspect, admire, care for, consider:--(make) inquire (-ry), (make) search, seek out.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1239:--inquire, make search.
from 1239; beef cattle or an animal of the ox family of either gender (as used for plowing); collectively, a herd:-- beeve, bull (+ -ock), + calf, + cow, great (cattle), + heifer, herd, kine, ox.
from 1239; properly, dawn (as the break of day); generally, morning:--(+) day, early, morning, morrow.
intensive from 1239; a looking after:--seek out.
from 1239; properly, examination, i.e. (by implication) punishment:--scourged.

a primitive root; to search out (by any method, specifically in worship or prayer); by implication, to strive after:--ask, beg, beseech, desire, enquire, get, make inquisition, procure, (make) request, require, seek (for).
from 1245; a petition:--request.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1121; a son, grandson, etc.:--X old, son.
borrowed (as a title) from 1247; the heir (apparent to the throne):--son.
from 1305 (in its various senses); beloved; also pure, empty:--choice, clean, clear, pure.
or bar {bar}; from 1305 (in the sense of winnowing); grain of any kind (even while standing in the field); by extens. the open country:--corn, wheat.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1250; a field:--field.
from 1305; purify:--cleanness, pureness.
the same as 1252; vegetable lye (from its cleansing); used as a soap for washing, or a flux for metals:--X never so, purely.
a primitive root; (absolutely) to create; (qualified) to cut down (a wood), select, feed (as formative processes):-- choose, create (creator), cut down, dispatch, do, make (fat).
a variation of 4757; Berodak-Baladan, a Babylonian king:--Berodach-baladan.Birliy.
from 1254 and 8050; Jah has created; Berajah, an Israelite:--Beraiah.
by reduplication from 1250; a fowl (as fattened on grain):--fowl.
a primitive root, to hail:--hail.
from 1258; hail -hail ((stones)).
from 1258; hail; Bered, the name of a place south of Palestine, also of an Israelite:--Bered.
from 1258; spotted (as if with hail):--grisled.
a primitive root; to select; also (as denominative from 1250) to feed; also (as equivalent to 1305) to render clear (Eccl. 3:18):--choose, (cause to) eat, manifest, (give) meat.
passive participle from 1288; blessed; Baruk, the name of three Israelites:--Baruch.
probably of foreign origin; damask (stuff of variegated thread):--rich apparel.
of uncertain derivation; a cypress (?) tree; hence, a lance or a musical instrument (as made of that wood):--fir (tree).
a variation of 1265; the cypress (or some elastic tree):--fir.
from 1262; food:--meat.
or Berothay {bay-ro-that'-ee}; probably from 1266; cypress or cypresslike; Berothah or Berothai, a place north of Palestine:--Berothah, Berothai.
probably feminine plural from an unused root (apparently mean to pierce); holes; Birzoth, an Israelite:--Birzavith (from the marg.).
perhaps from the root of 1269; iron (as cutting); by extension, an iron implement:--(ax) head, iron.
from 1270; iron-hearted; Barzillai, the name of three Israelites:--Barzillai.
a primitive root; to bolt, i.e. figuratively, to flee suddenly:--chase (away); drive away, fain, flee (away), put to flight, make haste, reach, run away, shoot.
by transposition for 978; a Barchumite, or native of Bachurim:--Barhumite.
from 1262; fat:--fat.
probably by contraction from 882; Beri, an Israelite:--Beri.
of uncertain derivation; (only in the plural and with the article) the Berites, a place in Palestine:--Berites.
from 1254 (in the sense of 1262); fatted or plump:--fat ((fleshed), -ter), fed, firm, plenteous, rank.
feminine from 1254; a creation, i.e. a novelty:--new thing.
feminine from 1262; food:--meat.
from 1272; a bolt:--bar, fugitive.
or (shortened) bariach {baw-ree'-akh}; from 1272; a fugitive, i.e. the serpent (as fleeing), and the constellation by that name:--crooked, noble, piercing.
the same as 1281; Bariach, an Israelite:--Bariah.
apparently from the feminine of 7451 with a prepositional prefix; in trouble; Beriah, the name of four Israelites:-- Beriah.
patronymically from 1283; a Beriite (collectively) or descendants of Beriah:--Beerites.
from 1262 (in the sense of cutting (like 1254)); a compact (because made by passing between pieces of flesh):--confederacy, (con-)feder(-ate), covenant, league.
the same as 1285; Berith, a Shechemitish deity:--Berith.
feminine of 1253; vegetable alkali:--sope.

a primitive root; to kneel; by implication to bless God (as an act of adoration), and (vice-versa) man (as a benefit); also (by euphemism) to curse (God or the king, as treason):--X abundantly, X altogether, X at all, blaspheme, bless, congratulate, curse, X greatly, X indeed, kneel (down), praise, salute, X still, thank.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1288:--bless, kneel.
from 1288; a knee:--knee.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1290:--knee.
from 1288 and 410, God has blessed; Barakel, the father of one of Job's friends:--Barachel.
from 1288; benediction; by implication prosperity:--blessing, liberal, pool, present.
the same as 1293; Berakah, the name of an Israelite, and also of a valley in Palestine:--Berachah.
from 1288; a reservoir (at which camels kneel as a resting-place):--(fish-)pool.
or Berekyahuw {beh-rek-yaw'-hoo}; from 1290 and 3050; knee (i.e. blessing) of Jah; Berekjah, the name of six Israelites:--Berachiah, Berechiah.
(Aramaic) perhaps from 7313 with a prepositional prefix; properly, highly, i.e. surely; but used adversatively, however:--but, nevertheless, yet.
of uncertain derivation; Bera, a Sodomitish king:--Bera.
a primitive root; to lighten (lightning):--cast forth.
from 1299; lightning; by analogy, a gleam; concretely, a flashing sword:--bright, glitter(-ing sword), lightning.
the same as 1300; Barak, an Israelite:--Barak.
of uncertain derivation; Barkos, one of the Nethimim:--Barkos.
from 1300; a thorn (perhaps as burning brightly):--brier.
or barkath {baw-rek-ath'}; from 1300; a gem (as flashing), perhaps the emerald:--carbuncle.
a primitive root; to clarify (i.e. brighten), examine, select:--make bright, choice, chosen, cleanse (be clean), clearly, polished, (shew self) pure(-ify), purge (out).
probably from 7562 with a prepositional prefix; with wickedness; Birsha, a king of Gomorrah:--Birsha.
patrial from 1268; a Berothite, or inhabitant of Berothai:--Berothite.
from 1319; cheerful; Besor, a stream of Palestine:--Besor.
or (shortened) bsorah {bes-o-raw'}; feminine from 1319; glad tidings; by implication, reward for good news:--reward for tidings.
a primitive root; properly, to boil up; hence, to be done in cooking; figuratively to ripen:--bake, boil, bring forth, roast, seethe, sod (be sodden).
from 1310; boiled:--X at all, sodden.
of foreign derivation; Bishlam, a Pers.:--Bishlam.
from an unused root meaning to be fragrant; (compare 5561) the balsam plant:--spice.
or bosem {bo'-sem}; from the same as 1313; fragrance; by implication, spicery; also the balsam plant:--smell, spice, sweet (odour).
feminine of 1314 (the second form); fragrance; Bosmath, the name of a wife of Esau, and of a daughter of Solomon:-- Bashemath, Basmath.
of uncertain derivation; Bashan (often with the article), a region East of the Jordan:--Bashan.
feminine from 954; shamefulness:--shame.
a primitive root; to trample down:--tread.

a primitive root; properly, to be fresh, i.e. full (rosy, (figuratively) cheerful); to announce (glad news):--messenger, preach, publish, shew forth, (bear, bring, carry, preach, good, tell good) tidings.
from 1319; flesh (from its freshness); by extension, body, person; also (by euphem.) the pudenda of a man:--body, (fat, lean) flesh(-ed), kin, (man-)kind, + nakedness, self, skin.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1320:--flesh.
from 954; shame (the feeling and the condition, as well as its cause); by implication (specifically) an idol:--ashamed, confusion, + greatly, (put to) shame(-ful thing).

from 1129 (as feminine of 1121); a daughter (used in the same wide sense as other terms of relationship, literally and figuratively):--apple (of the eye), branch, company, daughter, X first, X old, + owl, town, village.
probably from the same as 1327; a bath or Hebrew measure (as a means of division) of liquids:--bath.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1324:--bath.
probably an orthographical variation for 1327; desolation:--waste.
feminine from an unused root (meaning to break in pieces); desolation:--desolate.
apparently from the same as 1326 and 410; destroyed of God; Bethuel, the name of a nephew of Abraham, and of a place in Palestine:--Bethuel. Compare 1329.
for 1328; Bethul (i.e. Bethuel), a place in Palestine:--Bethuel.
feminine passive participle of an unused root meaning to separate; a virgin (from her privacy); sometimes (by continuation) a bride; also (figuratively) a city or state:--maid, virgin.
masculine plural of the same as 1330; (collectively and abstractly) virginity; by implication and concretely, the tokens of it:--X maid, virginity.
from 1323 and 3050; daughter (i.e. worshipper) of Jah; Bithjah, an Egyptian woman:--Bithiah.
a primitive root; to cut in pieces:--thrust through.
a primitive root, to chop up:--divide.
from 1334; a section:--part, piece.
the same as 1335; Bether, a (craggy) place in Palestine:--Bether.
from 1323 and a masculine plural from 7227; the daughter (i.e. city) of Rabbah:--Bath-rabbim.
from 1334; (with the article) the craggy spot; Bithron, a place East of the Jordan:--Bithron.
from 1323 and 7651 (in the sense of 7650); daughter of an oath; Bath-Sheba, the mother of Solomon:--Bath- sheba.
from 1323 and 7771; daughter of wealth; Bath-shua, the same as 1339:--Bath-shua.
for 1343; haughty:--proud.
a primitive root; to mount up; hence, in general, to rise, (figuratively) be majestic:--gloriously, grow up, increase, be risen, triumph.
from 1342; lofty; figuratively, arrogant:--proud.
feminine from 1342; arrogance:--pride.
from 1342 and 410; majesty of God; Geuel, an Israelite:--Geuel.
from 1342; arrogance or majesty; by implication, (concretely) ornament:--excellency, haughtiness, highness, pride, proudly, swelling.
from 1342; the same as 1346:--arrogancy, excellency(-lent), majesty, pomp, pride, proud, swelling.
from 1342; the same as 1346:--excellent things, lifting up, majesty, pride, proudly, raging.
from 1342: haughty:--proud.

a primitive root, to redeem (according to the Oriental law of kinship), i.e. to be the next of kin (and as such to buy back a relative's property, marry his widow, etc.):--X in any wise, X at all, avenger, deliver, (do, perform the part of near, next) kinsfolk(-man), purchase, ransom, redeem(-er), revenger.
a primitive root, (rather identified with 1350, through the idea of freeing, i.e. repudiating); to soil or (figuratively) desecrate:--defile, pollute, stain.
from 1351; profanation:--defile.
feminine passive participle of 1350; redemption (including the right and the object); by implication, relationship:--kindred, redeem, redemption, right.

from an unused root meaning to hollow or curve; the back (as rounded (compare 1460 and 1479); by analogy, the top or rim, a boss, a vault, arch of eye, bulwarks, etc.:--back, body, boss, eminent (higher) place, (eye)brows, nave, ring.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1354:--back.
from 1461; a log (as cut out); also well or cistern (as dug):--beam, ditch, pit.
probably from 1461 (compare 1462); a locust (from its cutting):--locust.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to 1461; a pit (for wild animals) (as cut out):--den.
or (fully) Gowb {gobe'}; from 1461; pit; Gob, a place in Palestine:--Gob.
from an unused root meaning probably to collect; a reservoir; by analogy, a marsh:--marish, pit.
a primitive root; to soar, i.e. be lofty; figuratively, to be haughty:--exalt, be haughty, be (make) high(-er), lift up, mount up, be proud, raise up great height, upward.
from 1361; lofty (literally or figuratively):--high, proud.
from 1361; elation, grandeur, arrogance:--excellency, haughty, height, high, loftiness, pride.
or (fully) gabowahh {gaw-bo'-ah}; from 1361; elevated (or elated), powerful, arrogant:--haughty, height, high(-er), lofty, proud, X exceeding proudly.
from 1361; pride:--loftiness, lofty.

or (shortened) gbul {gheb-ool'}; from 1379; properly, a cord (as twisted), i.e. (by implication) a boundary; by extens. the territory inclosed:--border, bound, coast, X great, landmark, limit, quarter, space.
or (shortened) gbulah {gheb-oo-law'}; feminine of 1366; a boundary, region:--border, bound, coast, landmark. place.
or (shortened) gibbor {ghib-bore'}; intensive from the same as 1397; powerful; by implication, warrior, tyrant:-- champion, chief, X excel, giant, man, mighty (man, one), strong (man), valiant man.
feminine passive participle from the same as 1368; force (literally or figuratively); by implication, valor, victory:-- force, mastery, might, mighty (act, power), power, strength.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1369; power:--might.
from an unused root meaning to be high (in the forehead); bald in the forehead:--forehead bald.
from the same as 1371; baldness in the forehead; by analogy, a bare spot on the right side of cloth:--bald forehead, X without.
from the same as 1354; collective:--Gabbai, an Israelite:--Gabbai.
plural of 1356; cisterns; Gebim, a place in Palestine:--Gebim.
from an unused root (meaning to be convex); a goblet; by analogy, the calyx of a flower:--house, cup, pot.
from 1396; a master:--lord.
feminine of 1376; a mistress:--queen.
from an unused root (probably meaning to freeze); crystal (from its resemblance to ice):--pearl.
a primitive root; properly, to twist as a rope; only (as a denominative from 1366) to bound (as by a line):--be border, set (bounds about).
from 1379 (in the sense of a chain of hills); a mountain; Gebal, a place in Phoenicia:--Gebal.
the same as 1380; Gebal, a region in Idumaea:--Gebal.
: patrial from 1380; a Gebalite, or inhabitant of Gebal:--Giblites, stone-squarer.
from 1379; a twisted chain or lace:--end.
from an unused root meaning to be arched or contracted; hunch-backed:--crookbackt.
feminine from the same as 1384; curdled milk:--cheese.
from the same as 1384; a hump or peak of hills:--high.
from the same as 1375, a hillock; Geba, a place in Palestine:--Gaba, Geba, Gibeah.
by permutation for 1389; a hill; Giba, a place in Palestine:--Gibeah.
feminine from the same as 1387; a hillock:--hill, little hill.
the same as 1389; Gibah; the name of three places in Palestine:--Gibeah, the hill.
from the same as 1387; hilly; Gibon, a place in Palestine:--Gibeon.
prolonged from 1375; the calyx of a flower:--bolled.
patrial from 1391; a Gibonite, or inhabitant of Gibon:--Gibeonite.
from the same as 1375; hilliness; Gibath:--Gibeath.
patrial from 1390; a Gibathite, or inhabitant of Gibath:--Gibeathite.
a primitive root; to be strong; by implication, to prevail, act insolently:--exceed, confirm, be great, be mighty, prevail, put to more (strength), strengthen, be stronger, be valiant.
from 1396; properly, a valiant man or warrior; generally, a person simply:--every one, man, X mighty.
the same as 1397; Geber, the name of two Israelites:--Geber.
from 1396; the same as 1397; a person:--man.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1399:--certain, man.
(Aramaic) intensive of 1400; valiant, or warrior:--mighty.
intensive of 1399; Gibbar, an Israelite:--Gibbar.
from 1397 and 410; man of God; Gabriel, an archangel:--Garbriel.
feminine of 1376; mistress:--lady, mistress.
intensive from 1389; a hilly spot; Gibbethon, a place in Palestine:--Gibbethon.
probably by reduplication from 1342; a roof; by analogy, the top of an altar:--roof (of the house), (house) top (of the house).
from 1413 (in the sense of cutting); coriander seed (from its furrows):--coriander.
a variation of 1409; Fortune, a Babylonian deity:--that troop.
from 1464 (in the sense of distributing); fortune:--troop.
from 1464; Gad, a son of Jacob, including his tribe and its territory; also a prophet:--Gad.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1489; a treasurer:--treasurer.
by reduplication from 1413 (in the sense of cutting) cleft; Gudgodah, a place in the Desert:--Gudgodah.
a primitive root (compare 1464); to crowd; also to gash (as if by pressing into):--assemble (selves by troops), gather (selves together, self in troops), cut selves.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1413; to cut down:--hew down.
from an unused root (meaning to cut off); a border of a river (as cut into by the stream):--bank.
from 1413; a crowd (especially of soldiers):--army, band (of men), company, troop (of robbers).
or (feminine) gdudah {ghed-oo-daw'}; from 1413; a furrow (as cut):--furrow.
feminine participle passive of 1413; an incision:--cutting.

or (shortened) gadol {gaw-dole'}; from 1431; great (in any sense); hence, older; also insolent:--+ aloud, elder(-est), + exceeding(-ly), + far, (man of) great (man, matter, thing,-er,-ness), high, long, loud, mighty, more, much, noble, proud thing, X sore, (X ) very.
or (shortened) gdullah {ghed-ool-law'}; or (less accurately) gduwllah {ghed-ool-law'}; feminine of 1419; greatness; (concretely) mighty acts:--dignity, great things(-ness), majesty.
or (shortened) gidduph {ghid-doof'}; and (feminine) gidduphah {ghid-doo-faw'}; or gidduphah {ghid-doo-faw'}; from 1422; vilification:--reproach, reviling.
feminine passive participle of 1442; a revilement:--taunt.
from the same as 1415; a young goat (from browsing):--kid.
from 1409; fortunate; Gadi, an Israelite:--Gadi.
patronymically from 1410; a Gadite (collectively) or descendants of Gad:--Gadites, children of Gad.
intensive for 1424; Gaddi, an Israelite:--Gaddi.
from 1409 and 410; fortune of God; Gaddiel, an Israelite:--Gaddiel.
or gadyah {gad-yaw'}; the same as 1415; a river brink:--bank.
feminine of 1423; a young female goat:--kid.
from an unused root (meaning to heap up); a stack of sheaves; by analogy, a tomb:--shock (stack) (of corn), tomb.

a primitive root; properly, to twist (compare 1434), i.e. to be (causatively make) large (in various senses, as in body, mind, estate or honor, also in pride):--advance, boast, bring up, exceed, excellent, be(-come, do, give, make, wax), great(-er, come to...estate, + things), grow(up),increase, lift up, magnify(-ifical), be much set by, nourish (up), pass, promote, proudly (spoken), tower.
from 1431; large (literally or figuratively):--great, grew.
from 1431; magnitude (literally or figuratively):-- greatness, stout(-ness).
from 1431 (in the sense of twisting); thread, i.e. a tassel or festoon:--fringe, wreath.
from 1431; stout; Giddel, the name of one of the Nethinim, also of one of "Solomon's servants":--Giddel.
or (prolonged) Gdalyahuw {ghed-al-yaw'- hoo}; from 1431 and 3050; Jah has become great; Gedaljah, the name of five Israelites:--Gedaliah.
from 1431; I have made great; Giddalti, an Israelite:--Giddalti.
a primitive root; to fell a tree; generally, to destroy anything:--cut (asunder, in sunder, down, off), hew down.
from 1438; feller (i.e. warrior); Gidon, an Israelite:--Gideon.
from 1438; a cutting (i.e. desolation); Gidom, a place in Palestine:--Gidom.
from 1438; warlike (compare 1439); Gidoni, an Israelite:--Gideoni.
a primitive root; to hack (with words), i.e. revile:--blaspheme, reproach.
a primitive root; to wall in or around:--close up, fence up, hedge, inclose, make up (a wall), mason, repairer.
from 1443; a circumvallation:--wall.
: the same as 1444; Geder, a place in Palestine:--Geder.
or (fully) Gdowr {ghed-ore'}; from 1443; inclosure; Gedor, a place in Palestine; also the name of three Israelites:--Gedor.
from 1443; a circumvallation; by implication, an inclosure:--fence, hedge, wall.
feminine of 1447; enclosure (especially for flocks):--(sheep-) cote (fold) hedge, wall.
the same as 1448; (with the article) Gederah, a place in Palestine:--Gederah, hedges.
plural of 1448; walls; Gederoth, a place in Palestine:--Gederoth.
patrial from 1445; a Gederite, or inhabitant of Geder:--Gederite.
patrial from 1449; a Gederathite, or inhabitant of Gederah:--Gederathite.
dual of 1448; double wall; Gederothajim, a place in Palestine:--Gederothaim.
probably a clerical error for 2088; this:--this.
a primitive root; to remove (a bandage from a wound, i.e. heal it):--cure.
from 1455; a cure:--medicine.
a primitive root; to prostrate oneself:--cast self down, stretch self.
another form for 1460; the back:--back.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1460; the middle:--midst, same, there- (where-) in.
from 1342 (corresponding to 1354); the back; by analogy, the middle:--+ among, back, body.
a primitive root; to dig:--husbandman.
from 1461; the locust (from its grubbing as a larvae):-- grasshopper, X great.
of uncertain derivation; Gog, the name of an Israelite, also of some nothern nation:--Gog.
a primitive root (akin to 1413); to crowd upon, i.e. attack:--invade, overcome.
feminine of 1460; the back, i.e. (by extensive) the person:--body.
the same as 1465; exaltation; (figuratively) arrogance:--lifting up, pride.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1466:--pride.
a primitive root (compare 1494); properly, to shear off; but used only in the (figuratively) sense of passing rapidly:--bring, cut off.
or (shortened) gozal {go-zawl'}; from 1497; a nestling (as being comparatively nude of feathers):--young (pigeon).
probably from 1468; a quarry (as a place of cutting stones); Gozan, a province of Assyria:--Gozan.

rarely (shortened) goy {go'-ee}; apparently from the same root as 1465 (in the sense of massing); a foreign nation; hence, a Gentile; also (figuratively) a troop of animals, or a flight of locusts:--Gentile, heathen, nation, people.
prolonged for 1465; a body, whether alive or dead:--(dead) body, carcase, corpse.
or (shortened) golah {go-law'}; active participle feminine of 1540; exile; concretely and collectively exiles:--(carried away), captive(-ity), removing.
from 1473; captive; Golan, a place east of the Jordan:--Golan.
of uncertain derivation; a pit:--pit.
probably from 1598; protected; Guni, the name of two Israelites:--Guni.
patronymically from 1476; a Gunite (collectively with article prefix) or descendants of Guni:--Gunites.
a primitive root; to breathe out, i.e. (by implication) expire:--die, be dead, give up the ghost, perish.
a primitive root; properly, to hollow or arch, i.e. (figuratively) close; to shut:--shut.
from 1479; a corpse (as closed to sense):--body.

a primitive root; properly, to turn aside from the road (for a lodging or any other purpose), i.e. sojourn (as a guest); also to shrink, fear (as in a strange place); also to gather for hostility (as afraid):--abide, assemble, be afraid, dwell, fear, gather (together), inhabitant, remain, sojourn, stand in awe, (be) stranger, X surely.
or (shortened) gur {goor}; perhaps from 1481; a cub (as still abiding in the lair), especially of the lion:--whelp, young one.
the same as 1482; Gur, a place in Palestine:--Gur.
or (feminine) gorah {go-raw'}; a variation of 1482:--whelp.
from 1481 and 1168; dwelling of Baal; Gur- Baal, a place in Arabia:--Gur-baal.

or (shortened) goral {go-ral'}; from an unused root meaning to be rough (as stone); properly, a pebble, i.e. a lot (small stones being used for that purpose); figuratively, a portion or destiny (as if determined by lot):--lot.
or rather (by permutation) giysh {gheesh}; of uncertain derivation; a mass of earth:--clod.
from 1494; a fleece (as shorn); also mown grass:--fleece, mowing, mown grass.
of foreign derivation; treasurer:--treasurer.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1489:--treasurer.
a primitive root (akin to 1468); to cut off, i.e. portion out:--take.
feminine from 1494; a fleece:--fleece.
patrial from the unused name of a place apparently in Palestine; a Gizonite or inhabitant of Gizoh:--Gizonite.
a primitive root (akin to 1468); to cut off; specifically to shear a flock or shave the hair; figuratively to destroy an enemy:--cut off (down), poll, shave, ((sheep-)) shear(-er).
from 1494; shearer; Gazez, the name of two Israelites:--Gazez.
from 1491; something cut, i.e. dressed stone:--hewed, hewn stone, wrought.
a primitive root; to pluck off; specifically to flay, strip or rob:--catch, consume, exercise (robbery), pluck (off), rob, spoil, take away (by force, violence), tear.
from 1497; robbery, or (concretely) plunder:--robbery, thing taken away by violence.
from 1497; plunder, i.e. violence:--violence, violent perverting. . gozal. See 1469.
feminine of 1498 and mean the same: -that (he had robbed) (which he took violently away), spoil, violence.
from an unused root meaning to devour; a kind of locust:--palmer-worm.
from the same as 1501; devourer:--Gazzam, one of the Nethinim:--Gazzam.
from an unused root meaning to cut down (trees); the trunk or stump of a tree (as felled or as planted):--stem, stock.
a primitive root; to cut down or off; (figuratively) to destroy, divide, exclude, or decide:--cut down (off), decree, divide, snatch.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1504; to quarry; determine:--cut out, soothsayer.
from 1504; something cut off; a portion:--part, piece.
the same as 1506; Gezer, a place in Palestine:--Gazer, Gezer.
feminine of 1506; the figure or person (as if cut out); also an inclosure (as separated):--polishing, separate place.
from 1504; a desert (as separated):--not inhabited.
(Aramaic) from 1505 (as 1504); a decree:--decree.

(in the m patrial from 1507; a Gezerite (collectively) or inhabitants of Gezer; but better (as in the text) by transposition Girziy {gher-zee'}; patrial of 1630; a Grizite (collectively) or member of a native tribe in Palestine:--Gezrites.
probably from 1518; the external abdomen, belly (as the source of the faetus (compare 1521)):--belly.
or (feminine) gacheleth {gah-kheh'-leth}; from an unused root meaning to glow or kindle; an ember:--(burning) coal.
from an unused root meaning to burn; flame; Gacham, a son of Nahor:--Gaham.
from an unused root meaning to hide; lurker; Gachar, one of the Nethinim:--Gahar.
or (shortened) gay {gah'-ee}; probably (by transmutation) from the same root as 1466 (abbreviated); a gorge (from its lofty sides; hence, narrow, but not a gully or winter-torrent):--valley.
probably from 1464; a thong (as compressing); by analogy, a tendon:--sinew.
or (shortened) goach {go'-akh}; a primitive root; to gush forth (as water), generally to issue:--break forth, labor to bring forth, come forth, draw up, take out.
(Aramaic) or (shortened) guwach (Aramaic) {goo'- akh}; corresponding to 1518; to rush forth:--strive.
from 1518; a fountain; Giach, a place in Palestine:--Giah.
or (shortened) Gichown {ghee-khone'}; from 1518; stream; Gichon, a river of Paradise; also a valley (or pool) near Jerusalem:--Gihon.
or Gechaziy {gay-khah-zee'}; apparently from 1516 and 2372; valley of a visionary; Gechazi, the servant of Elisha:--Gehazi.

or (by permutation) guwl {gool}; a primitive root; properly, to spin round (under the influence of any violent emotion), i.e. usually rejoice, or (as cringing) fear:--be glad, joy, be joyful, rejoice.
from 1523; a revolution (of time, i.e. an age); also joy:--X exceedingly, gladness, X greatly, joy, rejoice(-ing), sort.
or giylath {ghee-lath'}; feminine of 1524; joy:--joy, rejoicing.
patrial from 1542; a Gilonite or inhabitant of Giloh:--Gilonite.
of uncertain derivation; Ginath, an Israelite:--Ginath.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1615; lime:--plaster.
from the same as 1487; lumpish; Geshan, an Israelite:--Geshan.
from 1556; something rolled, i.e. a heap of stone or dung (plural ruins), by analogy, a spring of water (plural waves):--billow, heap, spring, wave.
from 1556; a cup for oil (as round):--bowl.
from an unused root meaning to shave; a barber:--barber.
from 1530 and 1158; fountain of ebullition; Gilboa, a mountain of Palestine:--Gilboa.
by reduplication from 1556; a wheel; by analogy, a whirlwind; also dust (as whirled):--heaven, rolling thing, wheel.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1534; a wheel:--wheel.
a variation of 1534:--wheel.
the same as 1536 (with the article as a properly, noun); Gilgal, the name of three places in Palestine:--Gilgal. See also 1019.
by reduplication from 1556; a skull (as round); by implication, a head (in enumeration of persons):--head, every man, poll, skull.
from an unused root probably meaning to polish; the (human) skin (as smooth):--skin.

a primitive root; to denude (especially in a disgraceful sense); by implication, to exile (captives being usually stripped); figuratively, to reveal:--+ advertise, appear, bewray, bring, (carry, lead, go) captive (into captivity), depart, disclose, discover, exile, be gone, open, X plainly, publish, remove, reveal, X shamelessly, shew, X surely, tell, uncover.
(Aramaic) or glat (Aramaic) {ghel-aw'}; corresponding to 1540:--bring over, carry away, reveal.
or (fully) Giyloh {ghee-lo'}; from 1540; open; Giloh, a place in Palestine:--Giloh.
feminine from 1556; a fountain, bowl or globe (all as round):--bowl, pommel, spring.
or (shortened) gillul {ghil-lool'}; from 1556; properly, a log (as round); by implication, an idol:--idol.
from 1563; clothing (as wrapped):--clothes.
feminine from 1540; captivity; concretely, exiles (collectively):--(they that are carried away) captives(-ity).
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1546:--captivity.
a primitive root; properly, to be bald, i.e. (causatively) to shave; figuratively to lay waste:--poll, shave (off).
or gilyown {ghil-yone'}; from 1540; a tablet for writing (as bare); by analogy, a mirror (as a plate):--glass, roll.
from 1556; a valve of a folding door (as turning); also a ring (as round):--folding, ring.
or (prolonged) Galiylah {gaw-lee-law'}; the same as 1550; a circle (with the article); Galil (as a special circuit) in the North of Palestine:--Galilee.
feminine of 1550; a circuit or region:--border, coast, country.
plural of 1552; circles; Geliloth, a place in Palestine:--Geliloth.
plural of 1530; springs; Gallim, a place in Palestine:--Gallim.
perhaps from 1540; exile; Goljath, a Philistine:--Goliath.
a primitive root; to roll (literally or figuratively):--commit, remove, roll (away, down, together), run down, seek occasion, trust, wallow.
from 1556; dung (as in balls):--dung.
from 1556; a circumstance (as rolled around); only used adverbially, on account of:--because of, for (sake).
from 1556, in the sense of 1560; great; Galal, the name of two Israelites:--Galal.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to 1556; weight or size (as if rolled):--great.
a variation of 1557; dung (plural balls of dung):--dung.
from 1561; dungy; Gilalai, an Israelite:--Gilalai.

a primitive root; to be extinguished; figuratively, to expire or be dried up:--be extinct, consumed, put out, quenched.

a primitive root; to stab; by analogy, to starve; figuratively, to revile:--pierce, strike (thrust) through, wound.
from 1856; a stab; Deker, an Israelite:--Dekar.
apparently from the same as 1865; properly, a pearl (from its sheen as rapidly turned); by analogy, pearl-stone, i.e. mother-of-pearl or alabaster:--X white.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 1755; an age:--generation.
or dera)own {day-raw-one;}; from an unused root (meaning to repulse); an object of aversion:--abhorring, contempt.
(also dor-bawn'); of uncertain derivation; a goad:--goad.
apparently from 1858 and 1843; pearl of knowledge; Darda, an Israelite:--Darda.
of uncertain derivation; a thorn:--thistle.
of uncertain derivation; the south; poet. the south wind:--south.
from an unused root (meaning to move rapidly); freedom; hence, spontaneity of outflow, and so clear:--liberty, pure.

of Persian origin; Darejavesh, a title (rather than name) of several Persian kings:--Darius.

a primitive root; to tread; by implication, to walk; also to string a bow (by treading on it in bending):--archer, bend, come, draw, go (over), guide, lead (forth), thresh, tread (down), walk.

from 1869; a road (as trodden); figuratively, a course of life or mode of action, often adverb:--along, away, because of, + by, conversation, custom, (east-)ward, journey, manner, passenger, through, toward, (high-) (path-)way(-side), whither(-soever).

a primitive root; properly, to tread or frequent; usually to follow (for pursuit or search); by implication, to seek or ask; specifically to worship:--ask, X at all, care for, X diligently, inquire, make inquisition, (necro-)mancer, question, require, search, seek (for, out), X surely.
a primitive root; to sprout:--bring forth, spring.
from 1876; a sprout; by analogy, grass:--(tender) grass, green, (tender)herb.

a primitive root; to be fat; transitively, to fatten (or regard as fat); specifically to anoint; figuratively, to satisfy; denominatively (from 1880) to remove (fat) ashes (of sacrifices):--accept, anoint, take away the (receive) ashes (from), make (wax) fat.
from 1878; fat; figuratively, rich, fertile:--fat.
from 1878; the fat; abstractly fatness, i.e. (figuratively) abundance; specifically the (fatty) ashes of sacrifices:-- ashes, fatness.

from 1887 and 253; aha!:--ah, aha, ha.

a primitive root; to be vain in act, word, or expectation; specifically to lead astray:--be (become, make) vain.

only in plural, from an unused root meaning to be hard; ebony:--ebony.

a primitive root (compare 1901); to murmur (in pleasure or anger); by implication, to ponder:--imagine, meditate, mourn, mutter, roar, X sore, speak, study, talk, utter.

of which the feminine (beyond the Pentateuch) is hiyw {he}; a primitive word, the third person pronoun singular, he (she or it); only expressed when emphatic or without a verb; also (intensively) self, or (especially with the article) the same; sometimes (as demonstrative) this or that; occasionally (instead of copula) as or are:--he, as for her, him(-self), it, the same, she (herself), such, that (...it), these, they, this, those, which (is), who.

a primitive root (compare 1949); to make a loud sound like Engl. "hum"); by implication, to be in great commotion or tumult, to rage, war, moan, clamor:--clamorous, concourse, cry aloud, be disquieted, loud, mourn, be moved, make a noise, rage, roar, sound, be troubled, make in tumult, tumultuous, be in an uproar.

prolongation for 2004; themselves (often used emphatic for the copula, also in indirect relation):--X in, X such (and such things), their, (into) them, thence, therein, these, they (had), on this side, whose, wherein.

from 2040; demolition:--destruction.

from the same as 2036; a castle (from its height):--palace.
perhaps from 2022; mountaineer; Haran, the name of two men:--Haran.
a primitive root; to pull down or in pieces, break, &� destroy:--beat down, break (down, through), destroy, overthrow, pluck down, pull down, ruin, throw down, X utterly.

or Harariy (2 Sam. 23:11) {haw-raw-ree'}; or Haarariy (2 Sam. 23:34, last clause), {haw-raw-ree'}; apparently from 2042; a mountaineer:--Hararite.
perhaps from the same as 2828; wealthy; Hashem, an Israelite:--Hashem.
from 8085; announcement:--to cause to hear.
from 5413; a melting:--is melted.

presumed to be from an unused root meaning to bear guilt; crime:--X strange.
