from 2938; properly, a taste, i.e. (figuratively) perception; by implication, intelligence; transitively, a mandate:-- advice, behaviour, decree, discretion, judgment, reason, taste, understanding.
(Aramaic) from 2939; properly, a taste, i.e. (as in 2940) a judicial sentence:--account, X to be commanded, commandment, matter.

(Aramaic) from 2939, and equivalent to 2941; properly, flavor; figuratively, judgment (both subjective and objective); hence, account (both subj. and obj.):--+ chancellor, + command, commandment, decree, + regard, taste, wisdom.
a primitive root; to load a beast:--lade.
a primitive root; to stab:--thrust through.
from 2952 (perhaps referring to the tripping gait of children); a family (mostly used collectively in the singular):--(little) children (ones), families.
a primitive root; to flatten out or extend (as a tent); figuratively, to nurse a child (as promotive of growth); or perhaps a denom. from 2947, from dandling on the palms:--span, swaddle.
from 2946; a spread of the hand, i.e. a palm- breadth (not "span" of the fingers); architecturally, a corbel (as a supporting palm):--coping, hand-breadth.
from 2946 (the same as 2947):--hand-breadth (broad).
from 2946; nursing:--span long.
a primitive root; properly, to stick on as a patch; figuratively, to impute falsely:--forge(-r), sew up.
of foreign derivation; a military governor:--captain.
a primitive root; apparently to trip (with short steps) coquettishly:--mince.
(Aramaic) from a root corresponding to 6852, and meaning the same as 6856; a finger-nail; also a hoof or claw:--nail.
a primitive root; properly, apparently to be thick; figuratively, to be stupid:--be fat.
probably from 5197; a dropping (of ointment); Taphath, an Israelitess:--Taphath.
a primitive root; to drive on; figuratively, to follow close:--continual.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 2956; to expel:--drive.
a variation of 2962; not yet:--before.
a primitive root; to overburden:--weary.
from 2959; a burden:--cumbrance, trouble.
from an unused root apparently meaning to be moist; properly, dripping; hence, fresh (i.e. recently made such):--new, putrefying.
from an unused root apparently meaning to interrupt or suspend; properly, non-occurrence; used adverbially, not yet or before:--before, ere, not yet.
a primitive root; to pluck off or pull to pieces; causatively to supply with food (as in morsels):--catch, X without doubt, feed, ravin, rend in pieces, X surely, tear (in pieces).
from 2963; something torn, i.e. a fragment, e.g. a fresh leaf, prey, food:--leaf, meat, prey, spoil.
from 2963; recently torn off, i.e. fresh:--pluckt off.
feminine (collectively) of 2964; prey, i.e. flocks devoured by animals:--ravin, (that which was) torn (of beasts, in pieces).
(Aramaic) from a name of foreign derivation; a Tarpelite (collectively) or inhabitants of Tarpel, a place in Assyria:--Tarpelites.
a primitive root; to desire:--long.
a primitive root; to be suitable:--appertain.
or Ya.azanyahuw {yah-az-an-yaw'-hoo}; from 238 and 3050; heard of Jah; Jaazanjah, the name of four Israelites:-- Jaazaniah. Compare 3153.
from 215; enlightener; Jair, the name of four Israelites:--Jair.
patronymically from 2971; a Jairite or descendant of Jair:--Jairite.
a primitive root; properly, to be slack, i.e. (figuratively) to be foolish:--dote, be (become, do) foolish(-ly).

a primitive root (probably rather the same as 2973 through the idea of mental weakness); properly, to yield, especially assent; hence (pos.) to undertake as an act of volition:--assay, begin, be content, please, take upon, X willingly, would.

of Egyptian origin; a channel, e.g. a fosse, canal, shaft; specifically the Nile, as the one river of Egypt, including its collateral trenches; also the Tigris, as the main river of Assyria:--brook, flood, river, stream.
a primitive root; to desist, i.e. (figuratively) to despond:--(cause to) despair, one that is desperate, be no hope.
or {yo-she-yaw'-hoo}; from the same root as 803 and 3050; founded of Jah; Joshijah, the name of two Israelites:-- Josiah.
from 857; an entry:--entrance.
from the same as 871; stepping; Jeatherai, an Israelite:--Jeaterai.
a primitive root; to bawl:--cry out.
from 2986; produce, i.e. a crop or (figuratively) wealth:--fruit, increase.
from 947; trodden, i.e. threshing-place; Jebus, the aboriginal name of Jerusalem:--Jebus.
patrial from 2982; a Jebusite or inhabitant of Jebus:--Jebusite(-s).
from 977; choice; Jibchar, an Israelite:--Ibhar.
from 995; intelligent; Jabin, the name of two Canaanitish kings:--Jabin.
a primitive root; properly, to flow; causatively, to bring (especially with pomp):--bring (forth), carry, lead (forth).
(Aramaic) corresponding to 2986; to bring:--bring, carry.
from 2986; a stream:--(water-)course, stream.
the same as 2988; Jabal, an antediluvian:--Jabal.
from 2986; having running sores:--wen.
from 1104 and 5971; devouring people; Jibleam, a place in Palestine:--Ibleam.
a primitive root of doubtful meaning; used only as a denominative from 2993; to marry a (deceased) brother's widow:--perform the duty of a husband's brother, marry.
from (the orig. of) 2992; a brother-in-law:--husband's brother.
feminine participle of 2992; a sister-in-law:--brother's wife, sister in law.
from 1129 and 410: built of God; Jabneel, the name of two places in Palestine:--Jabneel.
from 1129; a building; Jabneh, a place in Palestine:--Jabneh.
from 1129 and 3050; built of Jah; Jibnejah, an Israelite:--Ibneiah.
from 1129 and 3050; building of Jah; Jibnijah, an Israelite:--Ibnijah.
probably from 1238; pouring forth; Jabbok, a river east of the Jordan:--Jabbok.
from 1288 and 3050: blessed of Jah; Jeberekjah, an Israelite:--Jeberechiah.

a primitive root; to be ashamed, confused or disappointed; also (as failing) to dry up (as water) or wither (as herbage):--be ashamed, clean, be confounded, (make) dry (up), (do) shame(-fully), X utterly, wither (away).
from 3001; dry:--dried (away), dry.
the same as 3002 (also Yabeysh {yaw-bashe'}; often with the addition of 1568, i.e. Jabesh of Gilad); Jobesh, the name of an Israelite and of a place in Palestine:--Jobesh ((-Gilead)).
from 3001; dry ground:--dry (ground, land).
from the same as 1314; fragrant; Jibsam, an Israelite:--Jibsam.
a variation of 3004; dry ground:--dry land.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 3006; dry land:--earth.
from 1350; avenger; Jigal, the name of three Israelites:--Igal, Igeal.
a primitive root; to dig or plow:--husbandman.
from 3009; a plowed field:--field.
feminine from 1361; hillock; Jogbehah, a place East of the Jordan:--Jogbehah.
from 1431 and 3050; magnified of Jah; Jigdaljah, an Israelite:--Igdaliah.
a primitive root; to grieve:--afflict, cause grief, grieve, sorrowful, vex.
a primitive root (probably rather the same as 3013 through the common idea of dissatisfaction); to push away; -be removed.
from 3013; affliction:--grief, sorrow.
from 3025; fearful:--afraid, fearest.
probably from 1481; a lodging; Jagur, a place in Palestine:--Jagur.
from 3021; toil; hence, a work, produce, property (as the result of labor):--labour, work.
from 3021; tired:--weary.
from 1540; exiled; Jogli, an Israelite:--Jogli.
a primitive root; properly, to gasp; hence, to be exhausted, to tire, to toil:--faint, (make to) labour, (be) weary.
from 3021; earnings (as the product of toil); -that which he laboured for.
from 3021; tired; hence (transitive) tiresome:--full of labour, weary.
feminine of 3019; fatigue:--weariness.
a primitive root; to fear:--be afraid, fear.

(Aramaic) from a word derived from an unused root (meaning to gather) and a derivation of a root corresponding to 7717; heap of the testimony; Jegar-Sahadutha, a cairn East of the Jordan:--Jegar-Sahadutha.

a primitive word; a hand (the open one (indicating power, means, direction, etc.), in distinction from 3709, the closed one); used (as noun, adverb, etc.) in a great variety of applications, both literally and figuratively, both proximate and remote (as follows):--(+ be) able, X about, + armholes, at, axletree, because of, beside, border, X bounty, + broad, (broken-)handed, X by, charge, coast, + consecrate, + creditor, custody, debt, dominion, X enough, + fellowship, force, X from, hand(-staves, -y work), X he, himself, X in, labour, + large, ledge, (left-)handed, means, X mine, ministry, near, X of, X order, ordinance, X our, parts, pain, power, X presumptuously, service, side, sore, state, stay, draw with strength, stroke, + swear, terror, X thee, X by them, X themselves, X thine own, X thou, through, X throwing, + thumb, times, X to, X under, X us, X wait on, (way-)side, where, + wide, X with (him, me, you), work, + yield, X yourselves.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 3027:--hand, power.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 3034; to praise:--(give) thank(-s).
of uncertain derivation; Jidalah, a place in Palestine:--Idalah.
from the same as 1706; perhaps honeyed; Jidbash, an Israelite:--Idbash.
a primitive root; properly, to handle (compare 3034), i.e. to throw, e.g. lots:--cast.
from 3039; properly, affection; concretely, a darling object:--dearly beloved.

a primitive root; used only as denominative from 3027; literally, to use (i.e. hold out) the hand; physically, to throw (a stone, an arrow) at or away; especially to revere or worship (with extended hands); intensively, to bemoan (by wringing the hands):--cast (out), (make) confess(-ion), praise, shoot, (give) thank(-ful, -s, -sgiving).
from 3034; praised; Jiddo, an Israelite:--Iddo.
from 3034; thankful; Jadon, an Israelite:--Jadon.
from 3045; knowing; Jaddua, the name of two Israelites:--Jaddua.
or Yduthuwn {yed-oo-thoon'}; or Ydiythuwn {yed-ee-thoon'}; probably from 3034; laudatory; Jeduthun, an Israelite:--Jeduthun.
from the same as 1730; loved:--amiable, (well-)beloved, loves.
feminine of 3039; beloved; Jedidah, an Israelitess:--Jedidah.
from 3039 and 3050; beloved of Jah; Jedidejah, a name of Solomon:--Jedidiah.
from 3034 and 3050; praised of Jah; Jedajah, the name of two Israelites:--Jedaiah.
from 3045 and 410; knowing God; Jediael, the name of three Israelites:--Jediael.
from 1811; tearful; Jidlaph, a Mesopotamian:--Jidlaph.

a primitive root; to know (properly, to ascertain by seeing); used in a great variety of senses, figuratively, literally, euphemistically and inferentially (including observation, care, recognition; and causatively, instruction, designation, punishment, etc.) (as follow):--acknowledge, acquaintance(-ted with), advise, answer, appoint, assuredly, be aware, (un-)awares, can(-not), certainly, comprehend, consider, X could they, cunning, declare, be diligent, (can, cause to) discern, discover, endued with, familiar friend, famous, feel, can have, be (ig-)norant, instruct, kinsfolk, kinsman, (cause to let, make) know, (come to give, have, take) knowledge, have (knowledge), (be, make, make to be, make self) known, + be learned, + lie by man, mark, perceive, privy to, X prognosticator, regard, have respect, skilful, shew, can (man of) skill, be sure, of a surety, teach, (can) tell, understand, have (understanding), X will be, wist, wit, wot.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 3045:--certify, know, make known, teach.
from 3045; knowing; Jada, an Israelite:--Jada.
from 3045 and 3050; Jah has known; Jedajah, the name of two Israelites:--Jedaiah.
from 3045; properly, a knowing one; specifically, a conjurer; (by impl) a ghost:--wizard.
contraction for 3068, and meaning the same; Jah, the sacred name:--Jah, the Lord, most vehement. Compare names in "-iah," "- jah."
a primitive root; to give (whether literal or figurative); generally, to put; imperatively (reflexive) come:--ascribe, bring, come on, give, go, set, take.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 3051; -deliver, give, lay, + prolong, pay, yield.
from 3051; properly, what is given (by Providence), i.e. a lot:--burden.
denominative from a form corresponding to 3061; to Judaize, i.e. become Jewish:--become Jews.
a briefer form of one corresponding to 3061; Jehud, a place in Palestine:--Jehud.
perhaps from a form corresponding to 3061; Judaistic; Jehdai, an Israelite:--Jehdai.
feminine of 3064; Jehudijah, a Jewess: -Jehudijah.
from 3068 and 1931; Jehovah (is) He; Jehu, the name of five Israelites:--Jehu.
from 3068 and 270; Jehovah-seized; Jehoachaz, the name of three Israelites:--Jehoahaz. Compare 3099.
from 3068 and (perhaps) 784; Jehovah-fired; Jehoash, the name of two Israelite kings:--Jehoash. Compare 3101.
(Aramaic) contracted from a form corresponding to 3063; properly, Judah, hence, Judaea:--Jewry, Judah, Judea.
(Aramaic) patrial from 3061; a Jehudaite (or Judaite), i.e. Jew:--Jew.
from 3034; celebrated; Jehudah (or Judah), the name of five Israelites; also of the tribe descended from the first, and of its territory:--Judah.
patronymically from 3063; a Jehudite (i.e. Judaite or Jew), or descendant of Jehudah (i.e. Judah):--Jew.
the same as 3064; Jehudi, an Israelite:--Jehudi.
feminine of 3064; the Jewish (used adverbially) language:--in the Jews' language.
the same as 3066; Jewess; Jehudith, a Canaanitess:--Judith.
from 1961; (the) self-Existent or Eternal; Jehovah, Jewish national name of God:--Jehovah, the Lord. Compare 3050, 3069.
a variation of 3068 (used after 136, and pronounced by Jews as 430, in order to prevent the repetition of the same sound, since they elsewhere pronounce 3068 as 136):--God.
from 3068 and 7200; Jehovah will see (to it); Jehovah-Jireh, a symbolical name for Mount Moriah:--Jehovah- jireh.
from 3068 and 5251 with the prononimal suffix; Jehovah (is) my banner; Jehovah-Nissi, a symbolical name of an altar in the Desert:--Jehovah-nissi.
from 3068 and 6664 with pronominal suffix; Jehovah (is) our right; Jehovah-Tsidkenu, a symbolical epithet of the Messiah and of Jerusalem:--the Lord our righteousness.
from 3068 and 7965; Jehovah (is) peace; Jehovah-Shalom, a symbolical name of an altar in Palestine: -Jehovah-shalom.
from 3068 and 8033 with directive enclitic; Jehovah (is) thither; Jehovah-Shammah, a symbolic title of Jerusalem:--Jehovah-shammah.
from 3068 and 2064; Jehovah-endowed; Jehozabad, the name of three Israelites:--Jehozabad. Compare 3107.
from 3068 and 2603; Jehovah-favored; Jehochanan, the name of eight Israelites:--Jehohanan, Johanan. Compare 3110.
from 3068 and 3045; Jehovah-known; Jehojada, the name of three Israelites:--Jehoiada. Compare 3111.
from 3068 and 3559; Jehovah will establish; Jehojakin, a Jewish king:--Jehoiachin. Compare 3112.
from 3068 abbreviated and 6965; Jehovah will raise; Jehojakim, a Jewish king:--Jehoiakim. Compare 3113.
from 3068 and 7378; Jehovah will contend; Jehojarib, the name of two Israelites:--Jehoiarib. Compare 3114.
from 3201; potent; Jehukal, an Israelite: -Jehucal. Compare 3116.
from 3068 and 5068; Jehovah-largessed; Jehonadab, the name of an Israelite and of an Arab:--Jehonadab, Jonadab. Compare 3122.
from 3068 and 5414; Jehovah-given; Jehonathan, the name of four Israelites:--Jonathan. Compare 3129.
a fuller form of 3130; Jehoseph (i.e. Joseph), a son of Jacob:--Joseph.
from 3068 and 5710; Jehovah-adorned; Jehoaddah, an Israelite:--Jehoada.
or Yhowaddan {yeh-ho-ad-dawn'}; from 3068 and 5727; Jehovah-pleased; Jehoaddin or Jehoaddan, an Israelitess:--Jehoaddan.
from 3068 and 6663; Jehovah-righted; Jehotsadak, an Israelite:--Jehozadek, Josedech. Compare 3136.
from 3068 and 7311; Jehovah-raised; Jehoram, the name of a Syrian and of three Israelites:--Jehoram, Joram. Compare 3141.
from 3068 and 7650; Jehovah-sworn; Jehosheba, an Israelitess:--Jehosheba. Compare 3090.
a form of 3089; Jehoshabath, an Israelitess:--Jehoshabeath.
or Yhowshua {yeh-ho-shoo'-ah}; from 3068 and 3467; Jehovah-saved; Jehoshua (i.e. Joshua), the Jewish leader:--Jehoshua, Jehoshuah, Joshua. Compare 1954, 3442.
from 3068 and 8199; Jehovah-judged; Jehoshaphat, the name of six Israelites; also of a valley near Jerusalem:--Jehoshaphat. Compare 3146.
probably from the same as 2022; elated; hence, arrogant:--haughty, proud.
from 1984 and 410; praising God; Jehallelel, the name of two Israelites:--Jehalellel, Jehalelel.
from 1986 (in the sense of hardness); a precious stone, probably onyx:--diamond.
or Yahtsah {yah'-tsaw}; or (feminine) Yahtsah {yah-tsaw'}; from an unused root meaning to stamp; perhaps threshing-floor; Jahats or Jahtsah, a place East of the Jordan:--Jahaz, Jahazah, Jahzah.
from 3068 and 1; Jehovah-fathered; Joab, the name of three Israelites:--Joab.
from 3068 and 251; Jehovah-brothered; Joach, the name of four Israelites:--Joah.
a form of 3059; Joachaz, the name of two Israelites:--Jehoahaz, Joahaz.
from 3068 and 410; Jehovah (is his) God; Joel, the name of twelve Israelites:--Joel.
or Yoash (2 Chron. 24:1) {yo-awsh'}; a form of 3060; Joash, the name of six Israelites:--Joash.
perhaps a form of 3103, but more probably by erroneous transcription for 3437; Job, an Israelite:--Job.
from 2980; howler; Jobab, the name of two Israelites and of three foreigners:--Jobab.

or yobel {yob-ale'}; apparently from 2986; the blast of a horn (from its continuous sound); specifically, the signal of the silver trumpets; hence, the instrument itself and the festival thus introduced:--jubile, ram's horn, trumpet.
from 2986; a stream:--river.
from 2986; stream; Jubal, an antediluvian:--Jubal.
a form of 3075; Jozabad, the name of ten Israelites:--Josabad, Jozabad.
from 3068 and 2142; Jehovah-remembered; Jozacar, an Israelite:--Jozachar.
probably from 3068 and a variation of 2421; Jehovah-revived; Jocha, the name of two Israelites:--Joha.
a form of 3076; Jochanan, the name of nine Israelites:--Johanan.
a form of 3077; Jojada, the name of two Israelites:--Jehoiada, Joiada.
a form of 3078; Jojakin, an Israelite king:--Jehoiachin.
a form of 3079; Jojakim, an Israelite:--Joiakim. Compare 3137.
a form of 3080; Jojarib, the name of four Israelites:--Joiarib.
from 3068 contracted and 3513; Jehovah-gloried; Jokebed, the mother of Moses:--Jochebed.
a form of 3081; Jukal, an Israelite:--Jucal.

from an unused root meaning to be hot; a day (as the warm hours), whether literal (from sunrise to sunset, or from one sunset to the next), or figurative (a space of time defined by an associated term), (often used adverb):--age, + always, + chronicals, continually(-ance), daily, ((birth-), each, to) day, (now a, two) days (agone), + elder, X end, + evening, + (for) ever(-lasting, -more), X full, life, as (so) long as (... live), (even) now, + old, + outlived, + perpetually, presently, + remaineth, X required, season, X since, space, then, (process of) time, + as at other times, + in trouble, weather, (as) when, (a, the, within a) while (that), X whole (+ age), (full) year(-ly), + younger.
(Aramaic) corresponding to 3117; a day:--day (by day), time.
from 3117; daily:--daily, (by, in the) day(-time).

probably from the same as 3196; effervescing (i.e. hot and active); Javan, the name of a son of Joktan, and of the race (Ionians, i.e. Greeks) descended from him, with their territory; also of a place in Arabia:--Javan.
from the same as 3196; properly, dregs (as effervescing); hence, mud:--mire, miry.
a form of 3082; Jonadab, the name of an Israelite and of a Rechabite:--Jonadab.
probably from the same as 3196; a dove (apparently from the warmth of their mating):--dove, pigeon.
the same as 3123; Jonah, an Israelite:--Jonah.
patronymically from 3121; a Jevanite, or descendant of Javan:--Grecian.
active participle of 3243; a sucker; hence, a twig (of a tree felled and sprouting):--tender plant.
feminine of 3126; a sprout:--(tender) branch, young twig.

from 3123 and 482 and the plural of 7350; dove of (the) silence (i.e. dumb Israel) of (i.e. among) distances (i.e. strangers); the title of a ditty (used for a name of its melody):--Jonath-elem-rechokim.
a form of 3083; Jonathan, the name of ten Israelites:--Jonathan.
future of 3254; let him add (or perhaps simply active participle adding); Joseph, the name of seven Israelites:--Joseph. Compare 3084.
from active participle of 3254 and 3050; Jah (is) adding; Josiphjah, an Israelite:--Josiphiah.
perhaps feminine active participle of 3276; furthermore; Joelah, an Israelite:--Joelah.
apparently the active participle of 3259; appointer; Joed, an Israelite:--Joed.
from 3068 and 5828; Jehovah (is his) help; Joezer, an Israelite:--Joezer.
from 3068 and 5789; Jehovah-hastened; Joash, the name of two Israelites:--Joash.
a form of 3087; Jotsadak, an Israelite:--Jozadak.
a form of 3113; Jokim, an Israelite:--Jokim.
active participle of 3384; sprinkling; hence, a sprinkling (or autumnal showers):--first rain, former (rain).
